# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: balun
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:balun/abb] Incorporated in Switzerland as **ABB Ltd**, and headquartered in Zurich, it is dual-listed on the Nasdaq Nordic exchange in Stockholm, Sweden, and the SIX Swiss Exchange in Zurich., in addition to OTC Markets Group's pink sheets in the United States.
[src:balun/abb] For 30 years, it has been a part of the Fortune Global 500.
[src:balun/abb] Employees of ABB and its predecessor companies developed several technologies for generating, transmitting, and distributing electricity, as well as for enabling industrial automation.
[src:balun/abb] One is the miniature circuit breaker, invented by Hugo Stotz, which protects against fires and is found in almost every home.
[src:balun/abb] Predecessor ASEA was the first company to introduce a microprocessor into an industrial robot and it helped to develop the electric propulsion system "Azipod", which improved manoeuvrability by locating the propulsion system outside the hull.
[src:balun/abb] ABB is made up of around 20 divisions structured into four business areas: Electrification, Motion, Process Automation and Robotics & Discrete Automation.
[src:balun/abb] Previously, it had a large power grids business, which was sold to Hitachi in 2020, as well as a turbocharging business, that was spun off in 2022.
[src:balun/abb] Over the years, ABB made different acquisitions, with major ones in the 21st century including Baldor Electric, Thomas & Betts, and the GE Industrial Solutions division of General Electric.
[src:balun/abb] The company's activities have been the subject of controversy on multiple occasions.
[src:balun/abb] US-based Combustion Engineering, acquired by ABB in 1990, exposed the company to asbestos-related litigation, which led to ABB’s first-ever loss in 2001.
[src:balun/abb] A final claims settlement was reached in 2006.
[src:balun/abb] ABB has also been subject to three US Foreign Corrupt Practices Act bribery settlements in 2004, 2010, and 2022.
[src:balun/abb] Additionally, in 2001, an ABB entity pleaded guilty to bid rigging.
[src:balun/abb] During the 2010s, ABB largely focused its growth strategy on the robotics and industrial automation sectors.
[src:balun/abb] Before the sale of its Power Grids division to Hitachi in 2020, ABB was Switzerland's largest industrial employer.
[src:balun/abb] Allmänna Svenska Elektriska Aktiebolaget (ASEA, English translation: General Swedish Electrical Company Limited) was founded in 1883 in Västerås, Sweden by Ludvig Fredholm as manufacturer of electrical light and generators.
[src:balun/abb] Brown, Boveri & Cie (BBC) was formed in 1891 in Baden near Zurich, Switzerland by Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown and Walter Boveri as a Swiss group of electrical engineering companies producing AC and DC motors, generators, steam turbines and transformers.
[src:balun/abb] On 10 August 1987, ASEA and BBC announced they would merge to form ASEA Brown Boveri (ABB).
[src:balun/abb] The new corporation would remain headquartered in both Zurich, Switzerland and Västerås, Sweden, with each parent company holding 50 percent.
[src:balun/abb] The merger created a global industrial group with revenue of approximately $15 billion and 160,000 employees.
[src:balun/abb] The merger also included the Finnish company Strömberg that had been purchased by ASEA the same year.
[src:balun/abb] When ABB began operations on 5 January 1988, its core businesses included power generation, transmission and distribution; electric transportation; and industrial automation and robotics.
[src:balun/abb] In its first year, ABB undertook some 15 acquisitions, including the environmental control group Fläkt AB of Sweden, the contracting group Sadelmi/Cogepi of Italy, and the railway manufacturer Scandia-Randers A/S of Denmark.
[src:balun/abb] In 1989, ABB purchased an additional 40 companies, including Westinghouse Electric's transmission and distribution assets, and announced an agreement to purchase the Stamford, Connecticut-based Combustion Engineering (C-E).
[src:balun/abb] In 1990, ABB bought the robotics business of Cincinnati Milacron in the US.
[src:balun/abb] The acquisition expanded ABB's automated spot-welding operations in the American automotive industry.
[src:balun/abb] ABB's 1991 introduction of the IRB 6000 robot, demonstrated its increased capacity in this field.
[src:balun/abb] The first modular robot, the IRB 6000, can be reconfigured to perform a variety of specific tasks.
[src:balun/abb] The IRB 6000 was designed for spot-welding applications.
[src:balun/abb] In 1990, ABB also expanded into Australia when it acquired Commonwealth Engineering's plant in Dandenong, Melbourne.
[src:balun/abb] ABB continued to manufacture Comeng's B-class Melbourne tram at the plant.
[src:balun/abb] However, it did not continue manufacturing Comeng's Adelaide 3000 class railcar, which was manufactured by Clyde Engineering instead.
[src:balun/abb] In the early 1990s, ABB started expanding in Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:balun/abb] By the end of 1991, the company employed 10,000 people in the region.
[src:balun/abb] The following year, that number doubled.
[src:balun/abb] A similar pattern played out in Asia, where the reform and opening up in China and the lifting of some economic sanctions, helped open the region to a new wave of outside investment and industrial growth.
[src:balun/abb] In March 1992, ABB bought out the other shareholders of the formerly state owned BREL, making BREL a wholly owned subsidiary.
[src:balun/abb] It was subsumed into ABB Transportation in September 1992.
[src:balun/abb] Amid the wider privatisation of British Rail during the 1990s, BREL was sold via a management buyout, with management and employees owning 20% and ABB and Trafalgar House 40% each.
[src:balun/abb] At the time of the management buyout, BREL's locations comprised Crewe, York, and two separate works in Derby; Derby Locomotive Works was closed by 1991.
[src:balun/abb] By 1994, ABB had 30,000 employees across Asia as well as 100 plants, engineering, service and marketing centers; numbers that would continue to grow.
[src:balun/abb] Through the 1990s, ABB continued its strategy of targeted expansion in Eastern Europe, the Asia–Pacific region and the Americas.
[src:balun/abb] In 1995, ABB agreed to merge its rail engineering unit with that of Daimler-Benz of Germany; the goal of this arrangement was to create the world's largest maker of locomotives and railway cars.
[src:balun/abb] The new company, ABB Daimler-Benz Transportation (Adtranz), had an initial global market share of nearly 12 percent.
[src:balun/abb] The merge took effect on 1 January 1996.
[src:balun/abb] A few months following the start of the 1997 Asian financial crisis, ABB announced plans to accelerate its expansion in Asia as well as to improve the productivity and profitability of its Western operations.
[src:balun/abb] The company took an $850 million restructuring charge and shed 10,000 jobs as it scaled back some of its facilities in higher-cost countries and shifted resources towards emerging markets.
[src:balun/abb] In June 1998, ABB announced that it would acquire Sweden-based Alfa Laval's automation unit, which at the time was one of Europe's top suppliers of process control systems and automation equipment.
[src:balun/abb] In 1999, as a final step in the integration of the companies formerly known as ASEA and BBC, the directors unanimously approved a plan to create a unified, single class of shares in the group.
[src:balun/abb] That same year, ABB completed its purchase of Elsag Bailey Process Automation, a Netherlands-based maker of industrial control systems, for $2.1 billion.
[src:balun/abb] The acquisition increased ABB's presence in the high-tech industrial robotics and factory control system sectors, reducing its reliance on traditional heavy engineering sectors such as power generation and transmission.
[src:balun/abb] In 1999, the company sold its stake in the Adtranz train-building business to DaimlerChrysler.
[src:balun/abb] Instead of building complete locomotives, ABB's transportation activities shifted increasingly toward traction motors and electric components.
[src:balun/abb] That same year, ABB and France-based Alstom announced the merger of their power generation businesses in a 50-50 joint company, ABB Alstom Power.
[src:balun/abb] Separately, in December 1999, ABB agreed to sell its nuclear power business to British Nuclear Fuels of the United Kingdom.
[src:balun/abb] In 2000, ABB divested its interests in ABB Alstom Power and sold its boiler and fossil-fuel operations (including Gas turbines) to Alstom.
[src:balun/abb] In early 2002, ABB announced its first-ever annual loss, a $691 million net loss for 2001.
[src:balun/abb] The loss was caused by ABB's decision to double its provisions for settlement costs from $470 million to $940 million in asbestos-related litigation against its American subsidiary Combustion Engineering.
[src:balun/abb] The provisions were to cover claims linked to asbestos products sold by Combustion Engineering prior to its acquisition by ABB.
[src:balun/abb] At the same time, ABB's board announced it would seek the partial return of retirement pay from Goran Lindahl and Percy Barnevik, two former chief executive officers of the group.
[src:balun/abb] Barnevik received some $89 million in pension benefits when he left ABB in 2001; Lindahl, who succeeded Barnevik as CEO, had received $50 million in pension benefits, which ABB's board called "excessive".
[src:balun/abb] In 2004, ABB sold its upstream oil and gas business, ABB Vetco Gray, to a consortium of private equity investors for an initial sum of $925 million.
[src:balun/abb] ABB continued to play an active role in the oil and gas industry via its core automation and power technology businesses.
[src:balun/abb] In 2005, ABB delisted its shares from the London Stock Exchange and Frankfurt Stock Exchange.
[src:balun/abb] The following year, the company resolved its asbestos liabilities against its US subsidiaries, Combustion Engineering and ABB Lummus Global, Inc, for $1.43 billion.
[src:balun/abb] A three-part capital strengthening plan also aided in ABB's recovery.
[src:balun/abb] In August 2007, ABB Lummus Global, ABB's downstream oil and gas business, was sold to CB&I for $950 million.
[src:balun/abb] The sale led to ABB making an accelerated $204 million payment to the CE Asbestos PI Trust, a trust fund covering the asbestos liabilities of Combustion Engineering.
[src:balun/abb] In 2008, ABB agreed to acquire Kuhlman Electric Corporation, a US-based maker of transformers for the industrial and electric utility sectors.
[src:balun/abb] In November 2008, ABB acquired Ber-Mac Electrical and Instrumentation to expand its presence in Western Canada's oil and gas industries.
[src:balun/abb] In September 2010, the company bought K-TEK, a manufacturer of level measurement instruments, for $50 million; it was incorporated into ABB's Measurement Products business unit within ABB's Process Automation division.
[src:balun/abb] In July 2010, ABB in Cary, North Carolina received a $4.2 million grant from the US federal government to develop energy storing magnets.
[src:balun/abb] On 10 January 2011, ABB invested $10 million in ECOtality, a San Francisco-based developer of charging stations and power storage technologies, to enter North America's electric vehicle charging market.
[src:balun/abb] On 1 July of that year, the company announced its acquisition of Epyon B.V. of the Netherlands, a manufacturer of EV-charging infrastructure.
[src:balun/abb] In early 2011, ABB acquired Baldor Electric for $4.2 billion in an all-cash transaction as part of ABB's strategy to increase its market share in the North American industrial motors segment.
[src:balun/abb] On 30 January 2012, the company announced the acquisition of Thomas & Betts, a North American specialist in low voltage products for industrial, construction and utility applications, in a $3.9 billion cash transaction.
[src:balun/abb] On 15 June 2012, ABB completed its acquisition of commercial and industrial wireless technology specialists Tropos.
[src:balun/abb] In July 2013, ABB acquired Power-One in a $1 billion all-cash transaction to become the leading global manufacturer of solar inverters.
[src:balun/abb] That same year, Fastned selected ABB to supply more than 200 Terra fast-charging stations along highways in the Netherlands.
[src:balun/abb] On 6 July 2017, ABB announced it had completed its acquisition of Bernecker + Rainer Industrie-Elektronik (B&R), the largest independent provider of product and software-based open-architecture for industrial automation.
[src:balun/abb] During January 2018, ABB became the title partner of the ABB FIA Formula E Championship, the world's first fully electric international FIA motorsport series.
[src:balun/abb] On 30 June 2018, the company completed its acquisition of GE Industrial Solutions, General Electric's global electrification business.
[src:balun/abb] On 17 December 2018, ABB announced it had agreed to sell 80.1% of its Power Grids business to Hitachi; the former Power Grids division thus became a part of the Hitachi Group and was rebranded to Hitachi Energy.
[src:balun/abb] During December 2022, it was confirmed that Hitachi had acquired the remaining 19.9% of the business.
[src:balun/abb] In March 2020 ABB announced the intent to purchase Cylon Controls Ltd.
[src:balun/abb] The acquisition enhanced ABB Electrification business' position in the commercial buildings segment.
[src:balun/abb] Also in March 2020, ABB announced that it had agreed to sell its solar inverter business to Italian solar inverter manufacturer Fimer; the transaction includes all of ABB's manufacturing and R&D sites in Finland, Italy and India, along with 800 employees across 26 countries.
[src:balun/abb] In November 2021, ABB completed the sale of its Mechanical Power Transmission business to RBC Bearings Inc. for $2.9 billion in cash.
[src:balun/abb] The sale was part of ABB's broader strategy to streamline its business and reduce its range of activities.
[src:balun/abb] In July 2022, the company announced the spinoff of its turbocharging business to shareholders.
[src:balun/abb] The spinoff was completed in October 2022 when the business was listed on the SIX Swiss Exchange under the new name of Accelleron.
[src:balun/abb] During December 2022, ABB opened a new 67,000 square metre robotics factory in Shanghai following a $150 million investment.
[src:balun/abb] In May 2023, ABB announced that it had completed the acquisition of Siemens' low-voltage NEMA motors business, with manufacturing operations in Guadalajara, Mexico.
[src:balun/abb] At the time, the business employed around 600 people and generated revenues of approximately $63 million in 2021.
[src:balun/abb] In June 2023, ABB agreed to acquire smart home automation provider Eve Systems.
[src:balun/abb] In September 2023, ABB announced it would partner with the Well Done Foundation to monitor methane and greenhouse gas emissions from orphaned wells in the United States.
[src:balun/abb] In January 2024, ABB acquired Real Tech, a prominent Canadian company specializing in innovative optical sensor technology for real-time water monitoring and testing.
[src:balun/abb] It also acquired two start-ups, Sevensense and the R&D engineering firm Meshmind, to expand its activities in AI and software.
[src:balun/abb] As of 2025, ABB planned to rebrand all of its residential electrical product lines acquired from GE with the ABB ReliaHome brand.
[src:balun/abb] In October 2025, ABB agreed to sell its industrial robotics business to Softbank Group in a $5.4 billion deal—preempting plans to spin the division off as its own company in 2026.
[src:balun/abb] The business has approximately 7,000 employees and with revenues in 2024 of $2.3 billion, it represented about 7 percent of ABB Group revenues.
[src:balun/abb] In December 2025, it was announced ABB had completed its acquisition of Gamesa Electric's power electronics business in Spain from Siemens Gamesa, originally revealed in December 2024.
[src:balun/abb] The acquired portfolio includes power conversion products such as wind converters for doubly-fed induction generators (DFIG), industrial battery energy storage systems (BESS), and utility-scale solar inverters.
[src:balun/abb] In 1990, ABB launched Azipod, a family of electric propulsion systems that extends below the hulls of large ships, providing both thrust and steering functions.
[src:balun/abb] Developed in cooperation with the Finnish shipbuilder Masa-Yards, Azipod has demonstrated the viability of hybrid-electric power in seagoing vessels, while also increasing maneuverability, fuel efficiency and space efficiency.
[src:balun/abb] In 1998, ABB launched the FlexPicker, a robot using a three-armed delta design uniquely suited to the picking and packing industry.
[src:balun/abb] In 2000, ABB brought to market the world's first commercial high-voltage shore-to-ship electric power, at the Swedish port of Gothenburg.
[src:balun/abb] Supplying electricity to berthed ships from the shore enables vessels to shut down their engines while in port, significantly reducing noise, vibrations and carbon emissions.
[src:balun/abb] In 2004, ABB launched its Extended Automation System 800xA, an industrial system for the process industries.
[src:balun/abb] Today, the company is the global market leader in distributed control systems.
[src:balun/abb] In May 2013, ABB Sécheron SA joined with several groups in Geneva TOSA (Trolleybus Optimisation Système Alimentation, or in English, Trolleybus Power System Optimization) in a one-year demonstration of a trolleybus route using a novel charging system.
[src:balun/abb] Rather than overhead wires, charging is accomplished by fixed overhead devices located at stops along the route and at the terminus.
[src:balun/abb] Jean-Luc Favre, head of Rail ISI, discussed the promising role of improved electric transport technology in ABB.
[src:balun/abb] In 2014, ABB unveiled YuMi, a collaborative industrial dual-arm assembly robot that permits people and machines to work side by side, unlocking new potential for automation in a range of industries.
[src:balun/abb] In 2018, ABB unveiled the Terra High Power charger for electric vehicles, capable of delivering enough to charge in eight minutes to enable an electric car to travel 200 kilometers.
[src:balun/abb] In 2025, ABB Building Automation and Controls, a division of Electrification Smart Buildings, introduced ABB Ability BuildingPro, for smart building automation and management.
[src:balun/abb] It is designed as a fully integrated cloud-connected platform, and unifies HVAC, lighting, energy, and asset control under one interface.
[src:balun/abb] It is also said to have real-time visibility with AI and IoT-driven optimization, offering remote management across entire building portfolios.
[src:balun/abb] It has an open architecture and scalable edge-to-cloud design for interoperability and sustainability, enabling commercial buildings to achieve higher efficiency, lower operational costs, and improved occupant comfort.
[src:balun/abb] ABB's Electrification business area offers products and services from substation to socket.
[src:balun/abb] Customers include a wide range of industry and utility operations, plus commercial and residential buildings.
[src:balun/abb] The business has strong exposure to rapidly growing segments, including renewables, data centers and smart buildings.
[src:balun/abb] ABB Electrification offers technologies for low- and medium-voltage, including electric vehicle (EV) infrastructure, modular substations, distribution automation, power protection, wiring accessories, switchgear, enclosures, cabling, sensing and control.
[src:balun/abb] The acquisition of GE Industrial Solutions, which was completed in June 2018, further strengthened ABB's #2 global position in electrification.
[src:balun/abb] ABB's Motion business area provides a range of electrical motors, generators, drives and services, as well as integrated digital powertrain solutions.
[src:balun/abb] Motion is the #1 player in the market globally.
[src:balun/abb] In September 2023, it was announced ABB Motion had acquired a minority stake in the Burlington-headquartered wind turbine analytics software company, WindESCo.
[src:balun/abb] ABB's Robotics & Discrete Automation business area combines machine and factory automation systems, mainly from B&R, which ABB acquired in 2017, with a comprehensive robotics concepts and applications suite.
[src:balun/abb] ABB has installed over 300,000 robots globally.
[src:balun/abb] The Robotics & Discrete Automation business has been positioned to capture the opportunities associated with the "factory of the future" by providing services for flexible manufacturing and smart machinery.
[src:balun/abb] According to a 2019 ABB press release, their automation business is #2 globally.
[src:balun/abb] ABB is planning on expanding its innovation and production capacity by investing in a new robotics factory in Shanghai.
[src:balun/abb] The Process Automation business area provides a range of automation, electrification and digital offerings for process, hybrid and maritime industries, including industry-specific integrated control and software, as well as measurement and analytics services.
[src:balun/abb] The Power Grids business area offered components for the transmission and distribution of electricity, and incorporated ABB's manufacturing network for transformers, switchgear, circuit breakers, and associated high voltage equipment such as digital protective relays.
[src:balun/abb] The division was subdivided into the four business units High Voltage Products, Transformers, Grid Automation and Grid Integration.
[src:balun/abb] In 2010, ABB's North American headquarters in Cary, North Carolina, announced a new partnership with Sensus of Raleigh, North Carolina, to develop technologies to work together on smart grids.
[src:balun/abb] During 2014, ABB formed a joint venture with Hitachi to provide HVDC system solutions in Japan.
[src:balun/abb] In December 2018, ABB and Hitachi announced that the latter would buy ABB's Power Grids division for roughly $6.4 billion.
[src:balun/abb] Hitachi officially acquired 80.1% of the business in July 2020.
[src:balun/abb] Initially known as *Hitachi ABB Power Grids*, the new Hitachi subsidiary was rebranded as Hitachi Energy in October 2021.
[src:balun/abb] The transaction was one of Hitachi's biggest-ever deals, as it shifted focus to a higher-growth market for electricity networks.
[src:balun/abb] Hitachi acquired the remainder of the company from ABB in 2022.
[src:balun/abb] In July 2021, ABB confirmed the sale of its mechanical power transmission business, Dodge, to American company RBC Bearings Incorporated for $2.9bn.
[src:balun/abb] BREL was the first division of British Rail to be privatised as part of a phased plan initiated by the third Thatcher ministry.
[src:balun/abb] ABB took over two rolling stock manufacturing facilities from BREL; the Derby Litchurch Lane Works and York Carriage Works.
[src:balun/abb] Additionally, ABB took over Crewe Works in a purely maintenance capacity.
[src:balun/abb] During September 1992, ABB Group purchased the stakes of the other members of the consortium to become the sole owner with the business rebranded ABB Transportation.
[src:balun/abb] The first trains produced at either facility under ABB ownership were for an order for 22 three-carriage Class 320 electric multiple units, built at ABB York for Glasgow's suburban railways in 1990.
[src:balun/abb] That same year, ABB York finished an order for five similar four-car Class 322 units for the new Stansted Express service.
[src:balun/abb] Between 1990 and 1991, ABB York built 24 two-car Class 456 third rail trains for Network SouthEast services out of London Waterloo.
[src:balun/abb] A further order for 97 four-car Class 465 units was completed at ABB York for Network SouthEast services in and around Kent between 1991 and 1994.
[src:balun/abb] Numerous diesel multiple units were also built at ABB York, including 76 Class 165 suburban units for Chiltern Main Line and Great Western Main Line commuter services between 1990 and 1992, followed by 21 Class 166 three-car express units for longer-distance services out of London Paddington.
[src:balun/abb] In 1995, ABB Derby built 16 four-car Class 325 electric freight multiple units for the Royal Mail to replace their ageing fleet of parcels carriages.
[src:balun/abb] During the mid-1990s, in a bid to expand their international portfolio, both the Derby and York plants completed a number of ABB Eurotram light rail vehicles for the Strasbourg tramway in France.
[src:balun/abb] The last trains to roll off the production line at ABB York were an order for 41 four-carriage Class 365 electric multiple units for Connex South Eastern and West Anglia Great Northern services between 1994 and 1995.
[src:balun/abb] Following the privatisation of British Rail, ABB encountered a decline in train orders, largely due to increased competition from competing manufacturers and no longer having a monopoly on rolling stock production in the British market.
[src:balun/abb] During 1997, Adtranz unveiled the Class 168 train for Chiltern Railways.
[src:balun/abb] The design of the Class 168 would subsequently be further developed into the Turbostar and Electrostar families of trains, which in turn became the most successful rolling stock design on post-privatisation British railways by number of units sold.
[src:balun/abb] During 1999, ABB sold its 50% stake in Adtranz to Daimler for $472 million, thus exiting the rolling stock manufacturing sector.
[src:balun/abb] Shortly thereafter, Daimler sold the Adtranz unit to Bombardier Transportation.
[src:balun/abb] Bailey, Bailey Controls developed the world's first steam boiler meter before becoming an industry leader in control and instrumentation of automated processes.
[src:balun/abb] In 1989 the company merged with the Italian Elsag Group which also produced automation control and instrumentation devices.
[src:balun/abb] Elsag Bailey Process Automation would be acquired by ABB in 1999.
[src:balun/abb] In 1994 Fischer & Porter was acquired by Elsag Bailey Process Automation, which in turn was acquired by ABB in 1999.
[src:balun/abb] Since August 2024, Morten Wierod has been ABB's CEO.
[src:balun/abb] During September 2013, Ulrich Spiesshofer was named ABB's CEO, succeeding Joe Hogan.
[src:balun/abb] In August 2019, ABB announced industrial veteran Björn Rosengren would take over as CEO starting March 2020.
[src:balun/abb] Rosengren was then serving as CEO of Swedish mining-equipment giant Sandvik.
[src:balun/abb] In the meantime, ABB Chairman Peter Voser was appointed interim CEO on 17 April 2019, succeeding Ulrich Spiesshofer, who stepped down after five-and-a-half years.
[src:balun/abb] Voser was elected chairman of the board of directors in April 2015 and succeeded Hubertus von Grünberg, who had been chairman since May 2007.
[src:balun/abb] Jürgen Dormann was chairman from 2002 to 2007, and Percy Barnevik from 1999 to 2002.
[src:balun/abb] The largest single stake in the firm is held by the Swedish investment company Investor AB, controlled by the Wallenberg family, which holds 12.9%.
[src:balun/abb] Activist investor Cevian also holds a large stake in the company.
[src:balun/abb] In December 2022, ABB was charged by the U.S.
[src:balun/abb] Securities and Exchange Commission for violations of the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act in a bribery scheme in South Africa.
[src:balun/abb] It was ordered to pay a total of $460 million to U.S. authorities to settle criminal and civil charges.
[src:balun/abb] ABB paid more than $37 million in bribes to a high-ranking Eskom official to influence contracts awarded by the state-owned electric utility company for work on the Kusile Power Station project between 2014 and 2017.
[src:balun/abb] The official had influence over the awarding of contracts for power projects in the country.
[src:balun/abb] In exchange for the bribes, ABB secured a $160 million contract to provide services related to cabling and installation work at Eskom's Kusile Power Station, one of the largest coal-fired power plants in the world.
[src:balun/abb] In a parallel case, the United States Department of Justice fined ABB $315 million to settle criminal charges.
[src:balun/abb] ABB had to pay $75 million in civil penalties to settle the SEC's charges.
[src:balun/abb] It was fined 4 million Francs by Swiss authorities.
[src:balun/abb] ABB also agreed to repay $104 million to Eskom it was paid in connection with Kusile.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The amateur radio service (*amateur service* and *amateur-satellite service*) is established by the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) through its Radio Regulations.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] National governments set technical and operational rules for transmissions and issue individual station licences with unique call signs.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Call signs must be used in transmissions, at least every ten minutes and at the end of the conversation.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Amateur radio operators must hold an amateur radio licence, granted after an examination that tests knowledge of radio theory, electronics, and national regulations.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Operators are authorised to transmit on frequency ranges allocated internationally as the *amateur radio bands*.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Within these bands they may use any frequency, though some are restricted to particular modes of voice, text, image, or data communications.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] This allows communication locally, nationally, worldwide, and even with stations in space.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In many countries, operators may also exchange radio communications between computers or transceivers connected through virtual private networks on the Internet.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Amateur radio is represented by the International Amateur Radio Union (IARU), which has three regions and includes national amateur radio societies in most countries.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In 2011 the American Radio Relay League (the U.S. national society) estimated that about 2 million people worldwide were active in amateur radio.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] About 830,000 amateur radio stations are in Region 2 (the Americas), about 750,000 in Region 3 (South and East Asia and the Pacific), and about 400,000 in Region 1 (Europe, the Middle East, the CIS and Africa).
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Radio amateurs have been credited with a number of advancements, notably the discovery of skywave propagation.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The origins of amateur radio can be traced to the late 19th century, but amateur radio as practised today began in the early 20th century.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The *First Annual Official Wireless Blue Book of the Wireless Association of America*, produced in 1909, contains a list of amateur radio stations.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] This radio callbook lists wireless telegraph stations in Canada and the United States, including 89 amateur radio stations.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] As with radio in general, amateur radio was associated with various amateur experimenters and hobbyists.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Amateur radio enthusiasts have significantly contributed to science, engineering, industry, and social services.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Research by amateur operators has founded new industries, like experimentation with quartz piezoelectric resonators from 1924 until about 1934, built economies, empowered nations, and saved lives in times of emergency.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Ham radio can also be used in the classroom to teach English, map skills, geography, math, science, and computer skills.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The term *ham* was originally a pejorative, used in professional wired telegraphy during the 19th century to mock operators with poor Morse code-sending skills ("ham-fisted").
[src:balun/amateur-radio] This term continued to be used after the invention of radio and the subsequent proliferation of amateur experimentation with wireless telegraphy; among both land-based and sea-based professional radio telegraphers, *ham* amateurs were considered a nuisance.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The use of *ham* to mean amateurish or unskilled survives to this day in another discipline— i.e.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The amateur radio community subsequently reclaimed the word as a label of pride, and by the mid-20th century it had lost its pejorative meaning.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Although not an acronym or initialism, it is occasionally written as "HAM" in capital letters.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Amateur radio combines communication, technical experimentation, and recreation.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Operators take part in contests, provide emergency service, build and modify equipment, and use transmission modes ranging from traditional Morse code to modern digital protocols.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Operators often join conversational groups and take part in scheduled on-air meetings called nets, coordinated by a net control station.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Nets may provide training for emergencies, operate as informal discussions, or focus on specialised topics.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] With battery- or generator-powered equipment, operators frequently provide communication during natural disasters when commercial services are unavailable.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Competitive activities include contests to contact as many stations as possible in a set period, and operating awards such as Summits on the Air, Worked All States, and Jamboree on the Air.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Operators also contribute to citizen science by collecting propagation data and supporting atmospheric science research.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The principal voice modes are frequency modulation (FM), single sideband (SSB), and amplitude modulation (AM).
[src:balun/amateur-radio] FM offers high audio quality, SSB is efficient for long-distance use, and AM continues among users of vintage amateur radio equipment.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Radiotelegraphy using International Morse code, or Continuous Wave (CW), is one of the oldest modes in amateur radio.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Although largely replaced in professional services, it remains in use on shortwave bands because it functions under weak-signal conditions and employs internationally understood codes such as the Q code.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] CW is also used by hobbyists who build their own equipment (home construction) and by operators engaged in low-power operation, as CW transmitters are simple to construct and weak signals can often be received by ear.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Until 2003, Morse code proficiency was required under international regulations for access to frequencies below 30 MHz.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The requirement was withdrawn in the United States in 2007.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Personal computers have enabled new digital transmission modes.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Radioteletype (RTTY), once operated by mechanical devices, is now handled in software.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Packet radio, developed in the 1970s, uses protocols such as AX.25 and TCP/IP.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Later modes including PSK31 and FT8 allow efficient low-signal communication on shortwave bands.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Radio over IP (RoIP) applies Internet-based telephony techniques to radio.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] EchoLink and the Internet Radio Linking Project link repeaters and operators worldwide.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Other specialised modes support weak-signal communication.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Automatic link establishment (ALE) maintains networks on high-frequency bands, while the WSJT suite supports meteor scatter and moonbounce.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Fast-scan amateur television (ATV) adapts consumer video equipment to transmit images.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] It typically operates on the 70 cm (420–450 MHz) but may also use the 33 cm and higher frequencies.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Because of wide bandwidth requirements, ATV usually covers 30–100 km (20–60 mi).
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Linked repeater systems extend this range to several hundred kilometres.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Repeaters are often located on high ground or towers and may be linked by other amateur bands, landlines, or the Internet.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Operators can use amateur radio satellites, sometimes with only a hand-held transceiver.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Natural reflectors such as the Moon, the aurora borealis, and meteor trails are also used.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Licensed astronauts have also made contacts from the International Space Station through the ARISS programme.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Because radio signals can propagate across national borders, amateur radio is regulated by governments under international frameworks.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] National requirements generally follow standards set by the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) and World Radiocommunication Conferences.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Most countries require candidates to pass an examination that tests electronics, radio propagation, operating practices, and regulations.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Licensing grants access to a broader portion of the spectrum, additional communication modes, and higher transmitter power than unlicensed personal radio services such as CB, FRS, or PMR446.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Examination systems often include several levels, each granting wider frequency access and higher power limits.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In the United Kingdom and Australia, entry-level candidates must also complete a practical skills test to obtain the Foundation Licence, the first of three licensing stages.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Each licensee is normally assigned a unique call sign.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Some countries issue additional station licences, or recognise club and organisational licences.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Licences are generally valid only in the issuing country or in states with reciprocal agreements.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In some jurisdictions, a licence is also required to purchase or possess amateur radio equipment.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In the United States, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) issues three licence classes: Technician, General, and Amateur Extra.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Examinations are administered by accredited Volunteer Examiners through the FCC's Volunteer Examiner Coordinator system.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Higher licence classes provide access to more frequency bands and higher transmitter power.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The tests cover regulations, operating practices, electronics theory, equipment design, and safety.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Licences are valid for ten years, and the national question pools are published in advance and updated every four years.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Prospective amateur radio operators are examined on understanding of the key concepts of electronics, radio equipment, antennas, radio propagation, RF safety, and the radio regulations of the government granting the license.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] These examinations are sets of questions typically posed in either a short answer or multiple-choice format.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Examinations can be administered by bureaucrats, non-paid certified examiners, or previously licensed amateur radio operators.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The ease with which an individual can acquire an amateur radio license varies from country to country.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In some countries, examinations may be offered only once or twice a year in the national capital and can be inordinately bureaucratic (for example in India) or challenging because some amateurs must undergo difficult security approval (as in Iran).
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Currently, only Yemen and North Korea do not issue amateur radio licenses to their citizens.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Some developing countries, especially those in Africa, Asia, and Latin America, require the payment of annual license fees that can be prohibitively expensive for most of their citizens.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] A few small countries may not have a national licensing process and may instead require prospective amateur radio operators to take the licensing examinations of a foreign country.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In countries with the largest numbers of amateur radio licensees, such as Japan, the United States, Thailand, Canada, and most of the countries in Europe, there are frequent license examinations opportunities in major cities.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Granting a separate license to a club or organization generally requires that an individual with a current and valid amateur radio license who is in good standing with the telecommunications authority assumes responsibility for any operations conducted under the club license or club call sign.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] A few countries may issue special licenses to novices or beginners that do not assign the individual a call sign but instead require the newly licensed individual to operate from stations licensed to a club or organization for a period of time before a higher class of license can be acquired.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] A reciprocal licensing agreement between two countries allows licensed amateur radio operators from one country to operate stations in the other without obtaining a new licence.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In some cases, visiting operators may be issued a temporary local licence and call sign.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Some countries have bilateral or multilateral agreements that harmonise conditions, while others have no reciprocal arrangements.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Regional organisations, such as the Organization of American States, facilitate reciprocity through treaties, including the Inter-American Amateur Radio Service Convention.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Many people start their involvement in amateur radio on social media or by finding a local club.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Clubs often provide information about licensing, local operating practices, and technical advice.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Newcomers also often study independently by purchasing books or other materials, sometimes with the help of a mentor, teacher, or friend.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In North America, established amateurs who help newcomers are often referred to as "Elmers", as coined by Rodney Newkirk (W9BRD), within the ham community.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In addition, many countries have national amateur radio societies which encourage newcomers and work with government communications regulation authorities for the benefit of all radio amateurs.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] An amateur radio operator uses a **call sign** on the air to legally identify the operator or station.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In some countries, the call sign assigned to the station must always be used, whereas in other countries, the call sign of either the operator or the station may be used.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In certain jurisdictions, an operator may also select a *"vanity"* call sign although these must also conform to the issuing government's allocation and structure used for amateur radio call signs.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Some jurisdictions require a fee to obtain a vanity call sign; in others, such as the UK, a fee is not required and the vanity call sign may be selected when the license is applied for.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The FCC in the U.S. discontinued its fee for vanity call sign applications in September 2015, but reinstated it at $35 in 2022.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The combination of the three parts identifies the specific transmitting station, and the station's identification (its call sign) is determined by the license held by its operator.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In the case of commercial stations and amateur club stations, the operator is a corporation; in the case of amateur radio operators, the license-holder is a resident of the country identified by the first part of the call sign.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Many countries do not follow the ITU convention for the second-part digit.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In the United Kingdom the original calls **G0**xxx, **G2**xxx, **G3**xxx, **G4**xxx, were Full (A) License holders along with the last **M0**xxx full call signs issued by the City & Guilds examination authority in December 2003.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Additional Full Licenses were originally granted to (B) Licenses with **G1**xxx, **G6**xxx, **G7**xxx, **G8**xxx and 1991 onward with **M1**xxx call signs.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The newer three-level Intermediate License holders are assigned **2E0**xxx and **2E1**xxx, and the basic Foundation License holders are granted call signs **M3**xxx, **M6**xxx or **M7**xxx.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Instead of using numbers, in the U.K. the second letter after the initial 'G' or 'M' identifies the station's location; for example, a call sign **G7OOE** becomes **GM7OOE** and **M0RDM** becomes **MM0RDM** when the license holder is operating their station in Scotland.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Intermediate licence call signs are slightly different.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] They begin **2**z**0** and **2**z**1** where the z is replaced with one of the country letters, as above.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The exception however is for England, whose letter would be 'E'; however, letter 'E' *is* used, but *only* in intermediate-level call signs, and perplexingly never by the advanced licenses.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] For example **2E0** & **2E1** are used whereas the call signs beginning 'G' or 'M' for foundation and full licenses never use the 'E'.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In the United States, for non-vanity licenses, the numeral indicates the geographical district the holder resided in when the license was first issued.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Prior to 1978, US hams were required to obtain a new call sign if they moved out of their geographic district.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Call signs starting with 'V' end with a number after to indicate the political region; whereas the prefix **CY** indicates geographic islands.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] **CY** is for amateurs operating from Sable Island (**CY0**) or St.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Special permission is required to visit either of these: from Parks Canada for Sable and Coast Guard for St.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The last two or three letters of the call signs are typically the operator's choice (upon completing the licensing test, the ham writes three most-preferred options).
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Two-letter call sign suffixes require a ham to have already been licensed for 5 years.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Call signs in Canada can be requested with a fee.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Also, for smaller geopolitical entities, the digit at the second or third character might be part of the country identification.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] For example, **VP2**xxx is in the British West Indies, which is subdivided into **VP2E**xx Anguilla, **VP2M**xx Montserrat, and **VP2V**xx British Virgin Islands.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] **VP5**xxx is in the Turks and Caicos Islands, **VP6**xxx is on Pitcairn Island, **VP8**xxx is in the Falklands, and **VP9**xxx is in Bermuda.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Online callbooks or call sign databases can be browsed or searched to find out who holds a specific call sign.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] An example of an online callbook is QRZ.com.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Various partial lists of famous people who hold or held amateur radio call signs have been compiled and published.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Many jurisdictions (but not in the U.K. nor Europe) may issue specialty vehicle registration plates to licensed amateur radio operators.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The fees for application and renewal are usually less than the standard rate for specialty plates.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In most administrations, unlike other RF spectrum users, radio amateurs may build or modify transmitting equipment for their own use within the amateur spectrum without the need to obtain government certification of the equipment.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Radio amateurs have access to frequency allocations throughout the RF spectrum, usually allowing choice of an effective frequency for communications across a local, regional, or worldwide path.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The shortwave bands, or HF, are suitable for worldwide communication, and the VHF and UHF bands normally provide local or regional communication, while the microwave bands have enough space, or bandwidth, for amateur television transmissions and high-speed computer networks.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In most countries, an amateur radio license grants permission to the license holder to own, modify, and operate equipment that is not certified by a governmental regulatory agency.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] This encourages amateur radio operators to experiment with home-constructed or modified equipment.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The use of such equipment must still satisfy national and international standards on spurious emissions.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Amateur radio operators are encouraged both by regulations and tradition of respectful use of the spectrum to use as little power as possible to accomplish the communication.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] This is to minimise interference or electromagnetic compatibility (EMC) to any other device.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Although allowable power levels are moderate by commercial standards, they are sufficient to enable global communication.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Lower license classes usually have lower power limits; for example, the lowest license class in the UK (Foundation licence) has a limit of 25 W.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Power limits vary from country to country and between license classes within a country.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Output power limits may also depend on the mode of transmission.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In Australia, for example, 400 W may be used for SSB transmissions, but FM and other modes are limited to 120 W.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Certain countries permit amateur radio licence holders to hold a Notice of Variation that allows higher power to be used than normally allowed for certain specific purposes.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] E.g. in the UK some amateur radio licence holders are allowed to transmit using (33 dBw) 2.0 kW for experiments entailing using the moon as a passive radio reflector (known as Earth–Moon–Earth communication) (EME).
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The International Telecommunication Union (ITU) governs the allocation of communications frequencies worldwide, with participation by each nation's communications regulation authority.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] National communications regulators have some liberty to restrict access to these bandplan frequencies or to award additional allocations as long as radio services in other countries do not suffer interference.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In some countries, specific emission types are restricted to certain parts of the radio spectrum, and in most other countries, International Amateur Radio Union (IARU) member societies adopt voluntary plans to ensure the most effective use of spectrum.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In a few cases, a national telecommunication agency may also allow hams to use frequencies outside of the internationally allocated amateur radio bands.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In Trinidad and Tobago, hams are allowed to use a repeater which is located on 148.800 MHz.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] This repeater is used and maintained by the National Emergency Management Agency (NEMA), but may be used by radio amateurs in times of emergency or during normal times to test their capability and conduct emergency drills.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] This repeater can also be used by non-ham NEMA staff and REACT members.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In Australia and New Zealand, ham operators are authorized to use one of the UHF TV channels.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Similarly, amateurs in the United States may apply to be registered with the Military Auxiliary Radio System (MARS).
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Once approved and trained, these amateurs also operate on US government military frequencies to provide contingency communications and morale message traffic support to the military services.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Amateurs use a variety of voice, text, image, and data communication modes over radio.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Generally new modes can be tested in the amateur radio service, although national regulations may require disclosure of a new mode to permit radio licensing authorities to monitor the transmissions.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Encryption, for example, is not generally permitted in the amateur radio service except for the special purpose of satellite vehicle control uplinks.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The following is a partial list of the modes of communication used, where the mode includes both modulation types and operating protocols.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] In former times, most amateur digital modes were transmitted by inserting audio into the microphone input of a radio and using an analog scheme, such as amplitude modulation (AM), frequency modulation (FM), or single-sideband modulation (SSB).
[src:balun/amateur-radio] Beginning in 2017, increased use of several digital modes, particularly FT8, became popular within the amateur radio community.
[src:balun/amateur-radio] The following "modes" use no one specific modulation scheme but rather are classified by the activity of the communication.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The **American Radio Relay League** (**ARRL**) is the largest membership association of amateur radio enthusiasts in the United States.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL is a non-profit organization and was co-founded on April 6, 1914, by Hiram Percy Maxim and Clarence D.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL represents the interests of amateur radio operators before federal regulatory bodies, provides technical advice and assistance to amateur radio enthusiasts, supports a number of educational programs and sponsors emergency communications service throughout the country.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL has approximately 161,000 members.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In addition to members in the US, the organization claims over 7,000 members in other countries.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL publishes many books and a monthly membership journal called *QST*.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In 2023, the ARRL reported a significant increase in new amateur radio licensees in the United States, with over 30,000 new licenses issued for the first time since 2014.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL is the primary representative organization of amateur radio operators to the US government.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] It performs this function by lobbying the US Congress and the Federal Communications Commission.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL is also the international secretariat of the International Amateur Radio Union, which performs a similar role internationally, advocating for amateur radio interests before the International Telecommunication Union and the World Administrative Radio Conferences.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The organization is governed by a member-elected, volunteer Board of Directors.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Each director serves a three-year term and represents the members within their particular region of the country.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The national headquarters facilities are located in Newington, Connecticut.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Along with the administrative headquarters, the 7-acre (2.8 ha) site is home to amateur radio station W1AW.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL Field Organization carries out local and regional activities across the United States.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL is governed by a member-elected, volunteer Board of Directors.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The organization divides its membership into 15 Divisions, each representing a portion of the country.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] One Director and one vice-director are elected by the members of each Division to serve a three-year term.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Director elections are staggered so that one-third of the Directors and Vice Directors are up for election each year.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The Board of Directors manages policy direction for the organization as a whole.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The Board of Directors appoints an executive committee, led by the President and consisting of members of the ARRL Board of Directors, to make policy decisions between full Board meetings.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] ARRL's officers manage day-to-day administrative operation of the organization, led by the Chief Executive Officer.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] These paid officers hold their positions as long as the Board of Directors approve but have no vote on the Board.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Local and regional operational activities of the American Radio Relay League are carried out through its Field Organization.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The organization divides the 15 Divisions into 71 separate geographic regions called Sections.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Each Section has a similar team of one elected, volunteer Section Manager and several volunteer positions.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Section Managers are elected by the members living within the section for a two-year term.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The Section Manager appoints a team of volunteers.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] A Section Manager may optionally appoint one or more Assistant Section Managers.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] An important function of the ARRL Field Organization is organizing emergency communications in the event of civil or natural disaster.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL's Amateur Radio Emergency Service (ARES) program is organized through the ARRL Field Organization.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Each Section of the Field Organization has an appointed Section Emergency Coordinator.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARES organization supports training, establishes Memorandums of Understanding (MOU) with governmental and relief agencies, and organizes regular practice exercises.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] ARES has provided essential supplemental emergency communications innumerable times throughout the league's history.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In 1989, hundreds of amateurs responded to the Loma Prieta earthquake in the San Francisco Bay area putting in over 3000 volunteer hours in the first week.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In 2005, ARES, with hundreds of volunteer amateur radio operators, provided key communications assistance to recovery organizations and officials coordinating Hurricane Katrina disaster relief.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Over 2,000 Amateur Radio clubs are members of the ARRL Affiliated Club Program.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In 1914, Hiram Percy Maxim of Hartford, Connecticut, was a prominent businessman, engineer, and inventor (notably of the Maxim Silencer).
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] He was also an active radio amateur, with one of the best-equipped stations in the Hartford area.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] One night in April he attempted to send a message to another ham in Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] He had a one-kilowatt station (call 1WH), and Springfield was only 30 miles (48 km) away, well within his normal range.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] He was unable to make contact, and remembering that he knew another ham in Windsor Locks, about halfway, he asked him to relay the message.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] At that time, the maximum reliable range of a station was a few hundred miles, and so Maxim realized that a formally organized relay system would be of tremendous use to amateurs.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Maxim was a member of the Radio Club of Hartford, and he presented a plan for the organization of an "American Radio Relay League" at its April 1914 meeting.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The club agreed to sponsor the development of such an organization.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Tuska, the secretary of the Hartford Radio Club, developed application forms and sent them out to every amateur station they could think of.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] By September 1914 they had over 230 stations on the roster.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In early 1915, disagreements began to surface as to the role of the Hartford Radio Club in the new organization, and in February the ARRL split off from the club and incorporated under Connecticut law.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Finances were shaky, and most of the income came from sales of booklets, maps and message blanks.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] By March 1915, there were 600 stations on the roster, and due to improvements in equipment and operating ability, some of the better stations were claiming communication ranges of up to a thousand miles.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] It was apparent that the ARRL now needed some kind of bulletin to stay in touch with its members.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Maxim and Tuska agreed to personally finance it, and in December 1915 the first, 16-page issue of *QST* was sent free to all members.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Further issues would be supplied through subscription at $1 per year.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In 1916, with ARRL membership nearing a thousand, Maxim set up six trunk lines of relay stations, both east–west and north–south, and individual managers were appointed.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Messages were now being relayed over longer and longer distances, and in February 1917 a message was sent from New York to Los Angeles and an answer received in one hour and twenty minutes.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In 1917, the ARRL was reorganized to a more formal organization.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] A constitution was adopted, twelve directors and four officers were elected (including President Maxim and Secretary Tuska), and membership was opened to anyone interested in radio.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] No sooner had this happened than all amateurs received a letter from the Department of Commerce ordering them off the air and to dismantle all antennas, because the United States had entered World War I.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] During the war the ARRL facilitated the recruitment of amateurs into communications positions with the armed services, but had little else to do since all civilian experimentation with radio equipment was prohibited.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In November 1918 the Armistice was signed, but Congress introduced bills to put all radio operations in the United States under control of the Navy.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Maxim testified before Congressional committees and the League organized an effective grass roots campaign with thousands of individuals contacting their congressmen in opposition.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The bills were defeated, and in April 1919 amateurs were permitted to put up antennas again, but only for receiving.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Meanwhile, the League needed reorganization.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] A financing plan consisting of selling bonds to members was adopted and about $7500 was raised.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] *QST* was purchased from its owner, Clarence Tuska.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] ARRL continued to lobby Congress for the resumption of transmitting privileges, and after a number of protests and appeals, amateur radio was fully restored in November 1919.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The 1920s saw tremendous technical growth in radio.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Pushed both by wartime demands and by the growing commercialization of radio, equipment rapidly improved.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The use of spark gap technology quickly disappeared as the more efficient continuous wave system of generating radio-frequency energy and transmitting Morse Code became standard.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In 1923 a two-way contact between Connecticut and France bridged the Atlantic Ocean for the first time.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] With government uncertainty as to how to allocate both commercial and amateur frequencies, the ARRL kept discipline in amateur ranks so that spectrum was not unnecessarily occupied.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] They worked with Washington and the result was that amateurs received the orderly series of harmonic frequency bands that they largely hold today (originally 1.8, 3.5, 7, 14, 28, and 56 MHz; other bands have since been added and the 56 MHz allocation was changed to 50 MHz).
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Other activities during this time included transcontinental relays to quickly move messages across the United States, communications assistance in several emergencies, and encouragement for an amateur radio operator on an Arctic expedition of Donald B.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] MacMillan—perhaps the first beginnings of DXpeditions.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The League also began to act in an advisory capacity for the American delegations at international radio conferences.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In 1925 the International Amateur Radio Union was formed, and it remains headquartered at Newington.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The long-running Frankford Radio Club (W3BKX) was founded around 1927 and affiliated with ARRL in 1930.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In the 1930s the Great Depression took its toll on development.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] His callsign W1AW was licensed to the League and remains in use as the first-ever Memorial Station.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In 1937 the DXCC Award, for working 100 countries, was established, and it still is the premier achievement in amateur radio.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Operators, often under the ARRL Emergency Corps, helped at numerous disasters.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The League's *QST* magazine acted as a forum for experimenters in voice, television, and very high frequency work.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] During World War II, US amateurs were again told to leave the air.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL developed the government-approved War Emergency Radio Service, a Civil Defense system.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Thousands of League members, and many thousands more who received technical training through its publications, served in the conflict.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The end of the war brought a tremendous expansion of amateur radio as large amounts of war surplus equipment was available, many recently trained operators became active, and experiments began in such newly developed modes as single sideband and microwaves.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The 1950s saw the continued development of amateur radio and consequent growth of the ARRL.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] New civil defense systems and procedures were developed by the League, including regular communications between isolated service members and their families.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Equipment rapidly improved, although there was some trouble with television interference.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL and many of its members cooperated with scientists during the International Geophysical Year in 1957, measuring the effects of solar activity on propagation in the VHF band.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] By 1964 the positive influence of the ARRL was so evident that the United States issued a commemorative postage stamp on its 50th anniversary.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] As the League prepared for the future a new headquarters building was opened at Newington.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In May, June, and July 2024, various ARRL online systems (including the Logbook of the World and its educational website) went unavailable.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The organization didn't admit that the outage was caused by ransomware until it filed legally-mandated notifications of the data breach on July 11, more than two months after the breach started on May 3.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In August 2024, the organization confirmed that it paid a million dollar ransom to resolve the malware attack.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Sixteen radio amateurs have led the ARRL as president.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL has opposed regulatory support for Broadband over Power Lines, arguing that the power lines will radiate interfering radio energy, impeding amateur radio activities.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The League has filed several interference reports with the FCC.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL sued the FCC, claiming that the FCC violated the Administrative Procedure Act in creating its rules pertaining to BPL.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] On April 25, 2008, a US Court of Appeals agreed with the ARRL that the FCC violated the APA, especially by redacting data from the public that could have shed doubt on the FCC's decision.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] "It is one thing for the Commission to give notice and make available for comment the studies on which it relied in formulating the rule while explaining its non-reliance on certain parts," D.C.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] On April 11, 2025, ARRL filed comments in response to the FCC's request for public input on removing unnecessary regurump's executive orders asking for the same.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The American Radio Relay League offers several services to members that support their on-air operations.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] For members with an interest in DXing, the organization operates both incoming and out-going QSL bureaus for the exchange of QSL cards with stations in other countries.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Staff at the organization headquarters maintain and operates station W1AW, the Hiram Percy Maxim Memorial Station, as a living memorial to the "Father of Organized Amateur Radio".
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The W1AW station is used for regular Morse code training transmissions for those wishing to learn and also broadcasts a variety of bulletins of interest to radio amateurs.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL/VEC (Volunteer Examiner Coordinator) sponsors amateur radio license examinations for the three classes of U.S. amateur license.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] License classes and examinations are held in various locations throughout the year.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Although the FCC currently recognizes 14 different organizations as VECs, the VEC sponsored by the ARRL oversees about two-thirds of all U.S. amateur radio license examinations.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL provides dozens of publications and journals to both members and non-members.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] *QST* is the organization's monthly membership journal, named after a Morse code Q signal that means "calling all stations".
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The organization also publishes two bimonthly magazines of special interest: *QEX* for radio electronics experimenters, and the *National Contest Journal* for contesting enthusiasts.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL publishes various technical books and online courses.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Members of the organization also have access to a special Members Only section of the ARRL web site that includes technical documents, expanded product reviews of amateur radio equipment, expanded contesting information, and a searchable database of all league publications.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] A flagship annual publication, The *Radio Amateur's Handbook*, has been published since 1926.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL also publishes a series of manuals designed to assist interested persons in obtaining an amateur radio license or upgrading to a higher class of license.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL sponsors numerous amateur radio contests throughout the year with the biggest of these being November Sweepstakes and the International DX Contest.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Other contests and sponsored operating events include Straight Key Night, VHF Sweepstakes, UHF Contest, and 10 GHz and Up Contest.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The ARRL also participates as a Headquarters station for the IARU HF World Championship.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Field Day is an annual event organized by the ARRL that includes both a competitive element as well as an emphasis on emergency communications readiness and the promotion of amateur radio.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Criticisms of ARRL have included its support for less strict licensing requirements in the 2000s, which opponents consider a "dumbing down" of amateur radio or making it more like CB radio, moves allegedly made to gain additional membership.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Regulation by bandwidth favors these proprietary technologies at the expense of narrowband and open-standard digital modes (such as JT65, PSK31, RTTY, and CW).
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Many Amateur Radio operators who are seeking to develop and experiment with new technology see the ARRL as backing down too quickly on the regulation by bandwidth issue.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] An ARRL decision on November 14, 2017 to censure a member of its board of directors drew strong criticism from many Amateur Radio operators.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Numerous operators expressed concern that this decision profoundly undermines the principles of representational democracy and of openness and transparency.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] A December 2017 white paper critical of the ARRL's actions was published online by CQ.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] This censure was rescinded by the ARRL Board of Directors at its next board meeting, in July 2019.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The **Elser-Mathes Cup** was created in 1928 by U.S.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Amateurs Fred Johnson Elser (W6FB/W7OX) and Stanley M.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] Mathes (7OE/K1CY) to be awarded for the "First Amateur Two-Way Communication Earth & Mars".
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The cup is a Philippine Igorot wood carving, a bowl supported by two standing figures.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] In the American Radio Relay League (ARRL) and the Radio Amateurs of Canada (RAC), the Section Manager is an elected volunteer who implements and manages programs in the section.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The Section Manager is elected by the members of the organization who reside in the section and holds office for a two-year term.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] For each of the section's activities, the Section Manager appoints individuals to oversee the activities.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] These individuals are collectively referred to as *the cabinet*.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The Section Manager also appoints volunteers to serve within these program areas.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The volunteers in any given Section serve at the pleasure of the Section Manager.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] There are currently 71 sections in the ARRL, (United States) and 12 sections in the RAC (Canada).
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] An Affiliated Club Coordinator is the assistant to the Section Manager for radio club matters.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] One ACC is appointed in each section by the Section Manager to encourage club affiliation with the national organization on a section-wide basis.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The Section Traffic Manager is appointed by the Section Manager to supervise and coordinate traffic handling efforts within the National Traffic System and the section.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The Section Emergency Coordinator is the assistant to the Section Manager for amateur radio emergency communications preparedness.
[src:balun/american-radio-relay-league] The SEC is appointed by the Section Manager.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] An **amorphous metal transformer** (**AMT**) is a type of energy efficient transformer found on electric grids.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] The magnetic core of this transformer is made with a ferromagnetic amorphous metal.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] The typical material (Metglas) is an alloy of iron with boron, silicon, and phosphorus in the form of thin (e.g.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] These materials have high magnetic susceptibility, very low coercivity and high electrical resistance.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] The high resistance and thin foils lead to low losses by eddy currents when subjected to alternating magnetic fields.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] On the downside amorphous alloys have a lower saturation induction and often a higher magnetostriction compared to conventional crystalline iron-silicon electrical steel.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] In a transformer the no-load loss is dominated by the core loss.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] With an amorphous core, this can be 70–80% lower than with traditional crystalline materials.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] The loss under heavy load is dominated by the resistance of the copper windings and thus called copper loss.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] Here the lower saturation magnetization of amorphous cores tends to result in a lower efficiency at full load.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] Using more copper and core material it is possible to compensate for this.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] So high efficiency AMTs can be more efficient at low and high load, though at a larger size.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] The more expensive amorphous core material, the more difficult handling and the need for more copper windings make an AMT more expensive than a traditional transformer.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] The main application of AMTs are the grid distribution transformers rated at about 50–1000 kVA.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] These transformers typically run 24 hours a day and at a low load factor (average load divided by nominal load).
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] The no load loss of these transformers makes up a significant part of the loss of the whole distribution net.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] Amorphous iron is also used in specialized electric motors that operate at high frequencies of perhaps 350 Hz or more.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] More efficient transformers lead to a reduction of generation requirement and, when using electric power generated from fossil fuels, less CO2 emissions.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] This technology has been widely adopted by large developing countries such as China and India where labour cost is low.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] AMT are in fact more labour-intensive than conventional distribution transformers, a reason that explains a very low adoption in the comparable (by size) European market.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] These two countries can potentially save 25–30 TWh electricity annually, eliminate 6-8 GW generation investment, and reduce 20–30 million tons of CO2 emission by fully utilizing this technology.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] Kuwabara et al., Hitachi Review 60(2011) no.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] "SPC Note on T&D network loss reduction and energy saving plan" SPC Transportation and Energy Section, Document #123, 1997 (in Chinese).
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] Naidu, "Amorphous Metal Transformers—New Technology Developments", Keynote Speech, CBIP-AlliedSignal Seminar (India), April 1999.
[src:balun/amorphous-metal-transformer] Li, Jerry (2011), Review and The Future of Amorphous Metal Transformers in Asia - a brief industry update, AEPN.
[src:balun/antenna-boresight] In telecommunications and radar engineering, the **antenna boresight** is the axis of maximum gain (maximum radiated power) of a directional antenna.
[src:balun/antenna-boresight] For most antennas the boresight is the axis of symmetry of the antenna.
[src:balun/antenna-boresight] For example, for axial-fed dish antennas, the antenna boresight is the axis of symmetry of the parabolic dish, and the antenna radiation pattern (the main lobe) is symmetrical about the boresight axis.
[src:balun/antenna-boresight] Most antennas boresight axis is fixed by their shape and cannot be changed.
[src:balun/antenna-boresight] However phased-array antennas can electronically steer the beam, changing the angle of the boresight by shifting the relative phase of the radio waves emitted by different antenna elements, and even radiate beams in multiple directions (multiple boresights).
[src:balun/antenna-boresight] The term *boresight* came from high-gain antennas such as parabolic dishes, which produce narrow, pencil-shaped beams which are difficult to aim accurately at a distant receiving antenna.
[src:balun/antenna-boresight] These often are equipped with optical boresights to assist in aiming.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In radio-frequency engineering, an **antenna** (American English) or **aerial** (British English) is a structure used to convert alternating electric currents into radio waves for transmission, and to convert radio waves back into electric currents for reception.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] It is the interface between radio waves propagating through space and electric currents moving in metal conductors, used with a transmitter or receiver.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In transmission, a radio transmitter supplies an electric current to the antenna's terminals, and the antenna radiates the energy from the current as electromagnetic waves (radio waves).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In reception, an antenna intercepts some of the power of a radio wave in order to produce an electric current at its terminals, that is applied to a receiver to be amplified.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antennas are essential components of all radio equipment.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] An antenna is an array of conductor segments (elements), electrically connected to the receiver or transmitter.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antennas can be designed to transmit and receive radio waves in all horizontal directions equally (omnidirectional antennas), or preferentially in a particular direction (directional, or high-gain, or "beam" antennas).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] An antenna may include components not connected to the transmitter, parabolic reflectors, horns, or parasitic elements, which serve to direct the radio waves into a beam or other desired radiation pattern.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Strong directivity and good transmitting efficiency when transmitting are hard to achieve with antennas whose dimensions are much smaller than a half wavelength.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The first antennas were built in 1886 by German physicist Heinrich Hertz in his pioneering experiments to prove the existence of electromagnetic waves predicted by the 1867 electromagnetic theory of James Clerk Maxwell.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Hertz placed dipole antennas at the focal point of parabolic reflectors for both transmitting and receiving.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Starting in 1895, Guglielmo Marconi began development of antennas practical for long-distance wireless telegraphy and opened a factory in Chelmsford, England, to manufacture his invention in 1898.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] antenna receiving a radio wave: The electric field (E) of the wave excites oscillating currents (black arrows) in the receiver.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antenna radiating radio waves: The transmitter applies an alternating current (red arrows) to the rods, which charges them alternately positive and negative, emitting loops of electric field.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The arrows of the loops get reversed each time the current changes polarity.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The words *antenna* and *aerial* are used interchangeably.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Occasionally the equivalent term "aerial" is used to specifically mean an elevated horizontal wire antenna.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The origin of the word *antenna* relative to wireless apparatus is attributed to Italian radio pioneer Guglielmo Marconi.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In the summer of 1895, Marconi began testing his wireless system outdoors on his father's estate near Bologna and soon began to experiment with long wire "aerials" suspended from a pole.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In Italian a tent pole is known as *l'antenna centrale*, and the pole with the wire was simply called *l'antenna*.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Until then wireless radiating transmitting and receiving elements were known simply as "terminals".
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Because of his prominence, Marconi's use of the word *antenna* spread among wireless researchers and enthusiasts, and later to the general public.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antennas are required by any radio receiver or transmitter to couple its electrical connection to the electromagnetic field.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Radio waves are electromagnetic waves that carry signals through space at the speed of light; in free space they propagate without material absorption, apart from geometric spreading loss.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antennas can be classified as omnidirectional, radiating energy approximately equally in all horizontal directions, or directional, where radio waves are concentrated in some direction(s).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] A so-called beam antenna is *unidirectional* – designed for maximum response in the direction of the remote station they are aligned with – whereas many other antennas are intended to respond to stations in several directions, but are not truly omnidirectional.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Since antennas obey *reciprocity*, the same radiation pattern applies both to transmission as well as reception of radio waves.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] A hypothetical antenna that radiates equally in all directions (vertical as well as all horizontal angles) is called an *isotropic radiator*; however, *exact* uniformity cannot be accomplished in practical antennas, and is only rarely desired (e.g. emergency antennas for spacecraft).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Rather, for most terrestrial communications, there is an advantage in *reducing* radiation toward the sky or ground in favor of horizontal direction(s).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Several dipole elements of slightly different lengths can be stacked in parallel, into an antenna array such as the Yagi–Uda in order to focus their radiation into a single horizontal direction, perpendicular to the stack, thus termed a *beam antenna*.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] A half‑wave dipole antenna is a balanced element, with equal and opposite voltages and currents at its two terminals, and serves as a simple reference for analyzing many other antenna designs.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The vertical antenna is a *monopole* antenna, not balanced with respect to ground.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The ground (or any large conductive surface) plays the role of the second conductor of a monopole.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Since monopole antennas rely on a conductive surface, they may be mounted with a *ground plane* to approximate the effect of being mounted on the Earth's surface.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] More complex antennas increase the directivity of the antenna.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Additional elements in the antenna structure, which need not be directly connected to the receiver or transmitter, increase its directionality.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antenna "gain" describes the concentration of radiated power into a particular solid angle of space.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Unlike amplifier gain, which generally implies a net increase in signal power, antenna gain reflects a redistribution of power so that more is radiated in some directions and less in others, without increasing the total radiated power.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Unlike amplifiers, antennas are electrically "passive" devices which conserve total power, and there is no increase in total power above that delivered from the power source (the transmitter), only improved distribution of that fixed total.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] A phased array consists of two or more simple antennas which are connected together through an electrical network.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This often involves a number of parallel dipole antennas with a certain spacing.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Depending on the relative phase introduced by the network, the same combination of dipole antennas can operate as a "broadside array" (directional normal to a line connecting the elements) or as an "end-fire array" (directional along the line connecting the elements).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antenna arrays may employ any basic (omnidirectional or weakly directional) antenna type, such as dipole, loop or slot antennas.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Log‑periodic and other frequency‑independent antennas employ self‑similar structures in order to operate effectively over a wide range of frequencies (i.e., with wide bandwidth).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The most familiar example is the log-periodic dipole array which can be seen as a number (typically 10 to 20) of connected dipole elements with progressive lengths in an endfire array making it rather directional; it finds use especially as a rooftop antenna for television reception.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] On the other hand, a Yagi–Uda antenna (or simply "Yagi"), with a somewhat similar appearance, has only one dipole element with an electrical connection; the other parasitic elements interact with the electromagnetic field in order to realize a highly directional antenna but with a narrow bandwidth.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Even greater directionality can be obtained using *aperture antennas* such as the parabolic reflector or horn antenna.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Since high directivity in an antenna depends on it being large compared to the wavelength, highly directional antennas (thus with high antenna gain) become more practical at higher frequencies (UHF and above).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] At low frequencies (such as AM broadcast), arrays of vertical towers are used to achieve directionality and they will occupy large areas of land.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] For reception, a long Beverage antenna can have significant directivity.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] For non directional portable use, a short vertical antenna or small loop antenna works well, with the main design challenge being that of impedance matching.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] With a vertical antenna a *loading coil* at the base of the antenna may be employed to cancel the reactive component of impedance; small loop antennas are tuned with parallel capacitors for this purpose.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] An antenna *lead-in* is the transmission line, or feed line, that connects the antenna to a transmitter or receiver.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The "antenna feed" may refer to all components connecting the antenna to the transmitter or receiver, such as an impedance matching network in addition to the transmission line.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] A microwave antenna may also be fed directly from a waveguide in place of a (conductive) transmission line.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] An antenna counterpoise, or ground plane, is a structure of conductive material which improves or substitutes for the ground.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] It may be connected to or insulated from the natural ground.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In a monopole antenna, this aids in the function of the natural ground, particularly where variations (or limitations) of the characteristics of the natural ground interfere with its proper function.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Such a structure is normally connected to the return connection of an unbalanced transmission line such as the shield of a coaxial cable.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] An electromagnetic wave refractor in some aperture antennas is a component which due to its shape and position functions to selectively delay or advance portions of the electromagnetic wavefront passing through it.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The refractor alters the spatial characteristics of the wave on one side relative to the other side.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] It can, for instance, bring the wave to a focus or alter the wave front in other ways, generally in order to maximize the directivity of the antenna system.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This is the radio equivalent of an optical lens.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] An antenna coupling network is a passive network (generally a combination of inductive and capacitive circuit elements) used for impedance matching in between the antenna and the transmitter or receiver.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This may be used to minimize losses on the feed line, by reducing transmission line's standing wave ratio, and to present the transmitter or receiver with a standard resistive impedance needed for its optimum operation.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The feed point location(s) is selected, and antenna elements electrically similar to tuner components may be incorporated in the antenna structure itself, to improve the match.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] It is a fundamental property of antennas that most of the electrical characteristics of an antenna, such as those described in the next section (e.g. gain, radiation pattern, impedance, bandwidth, resonant frequency and polarization), are the same whether the antenna is transmitting or receiving.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This equivalence follows reciprocity theorem of electromagnetics.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Therefore, in discussions of antenna properties no distinction is usually made between receiving and transmitting terminology, and the antenna can be viewed as either transmitting or receiving, whichever is more convenient.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] A necessary condition for the aforementioned reciprocity property is that the materials in the antenna and transmission medium are linear and reciprocal.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] *Reciprocal* (or *bilateral*) means that the material has the same response to an electric current or magnetic field in one direction, as it has to the field or current in the opposite direction.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Most materials used in antennas meet these conditions, but some microwave antennas use high-tech components such as isolators and circulators, made of nonreciprocal materials such as ferrite.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] These can be used to give the antenna a different behavior on receiving than it has on transmitting, which can be useful in applications like radar.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The majority of antenna designs are based on the *resonance* principle.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This relies on the behaviour of moving electrons, which reflect off surfaces where the dielectric constant changes, in a fashion similar to the way light reflects when optical properties change.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In these designs, the reflective surface is created by the end of a conductor, normally a thin metal wire or rod, which in the simplest case has a *feed point* at one end where it is connected to a transmission line.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The conductor, or *element*, is aligned with the electrical field of the desired signal, normally meaning it is perpendicular to the line from the antenna to the source (or receiver in the case of a broadcast antenna).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The radio signal's electric component induces a voltage in the conductor.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This causes an electrical current to begin flowing in the direction of the signal's instantaneous field.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] When the resulting current reaches the end of the conductor, it reflects, which is equivalent to a 180 degree change in phase.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] If the conductor is ⁠ 1 /4⁠ of a wavelength long, current from the feed point will undergo 90 degree phase change by the time it reaches the end of the conductor, reflect through 180 degrees, and then another 90 degrees as it travels back.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] That means it has undergone a total 360 degree phase change, returning it to the original signal.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The current in the element thus adds to the current being created from the source at that instant.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This process creates a standing wave in the conductor, with the maximum current at the feed.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The ordinary half-wave dipole is probably the most widely used antenna design.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This consists of two ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength elements arranged end-to-end, and lying along essentially the same axis (or *collinear*), each feeding one side of a two-conductor transmission wire.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The physical arrangement of the two elements places them 180 degrees out of phase, which means that at any given instant one of the elements is driving current into the transmission line while the other is pulling it out.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The monopole antenna is essentially one half of the half-wave dipole, a single ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength element with the other side connected to ground or an equivalent ground plane (or *counterpoise*).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Monopoles, which are one-half the size of a dipole, are common for long-wavelength radio signals where a dipole would be impractically large.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Another common design is the folded dipole which consists of two (or more) half-wave dipoles placed side by side and connected at their ends but only one of which is driven.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The standing wave forms with this desired pattern at the design operating frequency, fo, and antennas are normally designed to be this size.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] However, feeding that element with 3 fo (whose wavelength is ⁠ 1 /3⁠ that of fo) will also lead to a standing wave pattern.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Thus, an antenna element is *also* resonant when its length is ⁠ 3 /4⁠ of a wavelength.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This is true for all odd multiples of ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This allows some flexibility of design in terms of antenna lengths and feed points.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antennas used in such a fashion are known to be *harmonically operated*.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Resonant antennas usually use a linear conductor (or *element*), or pair of such elements, each of which is about a quarter of the wavelength in length (an odd multiple of quarter wavelengths will also be resonant).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antennas that are required to be small compared to the wavelength sacrifice efficiency and cannot be very directional.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Since wavelengths are so small at higher frequencies (UHF, microwaves) trading off performance to obtain a smaller physical size is usually not required.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The quarter-wave elements imitate a series-resonant electrical element due to the standing wave present along the conductor.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] At the resonant frequency, the standing wave has a current peak and voltage node (minimum) at the feed.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In electrical terms, this means that at that position, the element has minimum impedance magnitude, generating the maximum current for minimum voltage.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This is the ideal situation, because it produces the maximum output for the minimum input, producing the highest possible efficiency.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Contrary to an ideal (lossless) series-resonant circuit, a finite resistance remains (corresponding to the relatively small voltage at the feed-point) due to the antenna's resistance to radiating, as well as any conventional electrical losses from producing heat.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Recall that a current will reflect when there are changes in the electrical properties of the material.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This leads to the concept of impedance matching, the design of the overall system of antenna and transmission line so the impedance is as close as possible, thereby reducing these losses.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Impedance matching is accomplished by a circuit called an antenna tuner or impedance matching network between the transmitter and antenna.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The impedance match between the feedline and antenna is measured by a parameter called the standing wave ratio (SWR) on the feedline.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Consider a half-wave dipole designed to work with signals with wavelength 1 m, meaning the antenna would be approximately 50 cm from tip to tip.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] If the element has a length-to-diameter ratio of 1000, it will have an inherent impedance of about 63 ohms resistive.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Using the appropriate transmission wire or balun, we match that resistance to ensure minimum signal reflection.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Feeding that antenna with a current of 1 Ampere will require 63 Volts, and the antenna will radiate 63 Watts (ignoring losses) of radio frequency power.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Now consider the case when the antenna is fed a signal with a wavelength of 1.25 m; in this case the current induced by the signal would arrive at the antenna's feedpoint out-of-phase with the signal, causing the net current to drop while the voltage remains the same.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Electrically this appears to be a very high impedance.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The antenna and transmission line no longer have the same impedance, and the signal will be reflected back into the antenna, reducing output.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This could be addressed by changing the matching system between the antenna and transmission line, but that solution only works well at the new design frequency.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The result is that the resonant antenna will efficiently feed a signal into the transmission line only when the source signal's frequency is close to that of the design frequency of the antenna, or one of the resonant multiples.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This makes resonant antenna designs inherently narrow-band: Only useful for a small range of frequencies centered around the resonance(s).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] It is possible to use simple impedance matching techniques to allow the use of monopole or dipole antennas substantially shorter than the ⁠ 1 /4⁠ or ⁠ 1 /2⁠ wave, respectively, at which they are resonant.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Sometimes the resulting (lower) electrical resonant frequency of such a system (antenna plus matching network) is described using the concept of *electrical length*.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] An antenna operated at a lower frequency than its self‑resonant frequency is then called an *electrically short antenna*.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] For example, at 30 MHz (10 m wavelength) a true resonant ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wave monopole would be almost 2.5 meters long, and using an antenna only 1.5 meters tall would require the addition of a loading coil.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Then it may be said that the coil has lengthened the antenna to achieve an electrical length of 2.5 meters.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] However, the resulting resistive impedance achieved will be quite a bit lower than that of a true ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wave (resonant) monopole, often requiring further impedance matching (a transformer) to the desired transmission line.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] For ever shorter antennas (requiring greater "electrical lengthening") the radiation resistance plummets (approximately according to the square of the antenna length), so that the mismatch due to a net reactance away from the electrical resonance worsens.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Or one could as well say that the equivalent resonant circuit of the antenna system has a higher Q factor and thus a reduced bandwidth, which can even become inadequate for the transmitted signal's spectrum.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Resistive losses due to the loading coil, relative to the decreased radiation resistance, entail a reduced electrical efficiency, which can be of great concern for a transmitting antenna, but bandwidth is the major factor that sets the size of antennas at 1 MHz and lower frequencies.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The power flux density of the field from a transmitting antenna decreases with distance according to the inverse-square law, reflecting the geometrical spreading of the wave.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] For a given incoming flux, the power captured by a receiving antenna is proportional to its *effective area*.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] A half‑wave dipole, for example, has an effective area of about 0.13 λ2 when viewed from broadside.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] For an already efficient antenna design, the effective area (and thus gain) in a given direction can be increased only by reducing the gain in other directions.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] If a half-wave dipole is not connected to an external circuit but rather shorted out at the feedpoint, then it becomes a resonant half-wave element which efficiently produces a standing wave in response to an impinging radio wave.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Because there is no load to absorb that power, it retransmits all of that power, possibly with a phase shift which is critically dependent on the element's exact length.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Thus such a conductor can be arranged in order to transmit a second copy of a transmitter's signal in order to affect the radiation pattern (and feedpoint impedance) of the element electrically connected to the transmitter.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antenna elements used in this way are known as passive radiators.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] A Yagi–Uda array uses passive elements to greatly increase gain in one direction (at the expense of other directions).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] A number of parallel approximately half-wave elements (of very specific lengths) are situated parallel to each other, at specific positions, along a boom; the boom is only for support and not involved electrically.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Only one of the elements is electrically connected to the transmitter or receiver, while the remaining elements are passive.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The Yagi produces a fairly large gain (depending on the number of passive elements) and is widely used as a directional antenna with an antenna rotor to control the direction of its beam.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] It suffers from having a rather limited bandwidth, restricting its use to certain applications.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] What's more, a phased array can be made "steerable", that is, by changing the phases applied to each element the radiation pattern can be shifted *without* physically moving the antenna elements.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] When a radio wave hits a large conducting sheet it is reflected (with the phase of the electric field reversed) just as a mirror reflects light.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Placing such a reflector behind an otherwise non-directional antenna will insure that the power that would have gone in its direction is redirected toward the desired direction, increasing the antenna's gain by a factor of at least 2.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Likewise, a corner reflector can insure that all of the antenna's power is concentrated in only one quadrant of space (or less) with a consequent increase in gain.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Practically speaking, the reflector need not be a solid metal sheet, but can consist of a curtain of rods aligned with the antenna's polarization; this greatly reduces the reflector's weight and wind load.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Specular reflection of radio waves is also employed in a parabolic reflector antenna, in which a *curved* reflecting surface effects focussing of an incoming wave toward a so-called feed antenna; this results in an antenna system with an effective area comparable to the size of the reflector itself.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Other concepts from geometrical optics are also employed in antenna technology, such as with the lens antenna.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The antenna's power gain (or simply "gain") also takes into account the antenna's efficiency, and is often the primary figure of merit.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antennas are characterized by a number of performance measures which a user would be concerned with in selecting or designing an antenna for a particular application.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] A plot of the directional characteristics in the space surrounding the antenna is its *radiation pattern*.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The frequency range or *bandwidth* over which an antenna functions well can be very wide (as in a log-periodic antenna) or narrow (as in a small loop antenna); outside this range the antenna impedance becomes a poor match to the transmission line and transmitter (or receiver).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Use of the antenna well away from its design frequency affects its radiation pattern, reducing its directive gain.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Generally an antenna will not have a feed-point impedance that matches that of a transmission line; a matching network between antenna terminals and the transmission line will improve power transfer to the antenna.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] A non-adjustable matching network will most likely place further limits the usable bandwidth of the antenna system.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] It may be desirable to use tubular elements, instead of thin wires, to make an antenna; these will allow a greater bandwidth.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Or, several thin wires can be grouped in a *cage* to simulate a thicker element.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This widens the bandwidth of the resonance.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Amateur radio antennas that operate at several frequency bands which are widely separated from each other may connect elements resonant at those different frequencies in parallel.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Most of the transmitter's power will flow into the resonant element while the others present a high impedance.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Another solution uses *traps*, parallel resonant circuits which are strategically placed in breaks created in long antenna elements.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] When used at the trap's particular resonant frequency the trap presents a very high impedance (parallel resonance) effectively truncating the element at the location of the trap; if positioned correctly, the truncated element makes a proper resonant antenna at the trap frequency.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] At substantially higher or lower frequencies the trap allows the full length of the broken element to be employed, but with a resonant frequency shifted by the net reactance added by the trap.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The bandwidth characteristics of a resonant antenna element can be characterized according to its *Q* where the resistance involved is the radiation resistance, which represents the emission of energy from the resonant antenna to free space.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The *Q* of a narrow band antenna can be as high as 15.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] On the other hand, the reactance at the same off-resonant frequency of one using thick elements is much less, consequently resulting in a *Q* as low as 5.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] These two antennas may perform equivalently at the resonant frequency, but the second antenna will perform over a bandwidth 3 times as wide as the antenna consisting of a thin conductor.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antennas for use over much broader frequency ranges are achieved using further techniques.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Adjustment of a matching network can, in principle, allow for any antenna to be matched at any frequency.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Thus the small loop antenna built into most AM broadcast (medium wave) receivers has a very narrow bandwidth, but is tuned using a parallel capacitance which is adjusted according to the receiver tuning.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] On the other hand, log-periodic antennas are *not* resonant at any single frequency but can (in principle) be built to attain similar characteristics (including feedpoint impedance) over any frequency range.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] These are therefore commonly used (in the form of directional log-periodic dipole arrays) as television antennas.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Gain is a parameter which measures the degree of directivity of the antenna's radiation pattern.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] A high-gain antenna will radiate most of its power in a particular direction, while a low-gain antenna will radiate over a wide angle.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] High-gain antennas have the advantage of longer range and better signal quality, but must be aimed carefully at the other antenna.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] An example of a high-gain antenna is a parabolic dish such as a satellite television antenna.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Low-gain antennas have shorter range, but the orientation of the antenna is relatively unimportant.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] An example of a low-gain antenna is the whip antenna found on portable radios and cordless phones.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antenna gain should not be confused with amplifier gain, a separate parameter measuring the increase in signal power due to an amplifying device placed at the front-end of the system, such as a low-noise amplifier.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The *effective area* or effective aperture of a receiving antenna expresses the portion of the power of a passing electromagnetic wave which the antenna delivers to its terminals, expressed in terms of an equivalent area.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] For instance, if a radio wave passing a given location has a flux of 1 pW / m2 (10−12 Watts per square meter) and an antenna has an effective area of 12 m2, then the antenna would deliver 12 pW of RF power to the receiver (30 microvolts RMS at 75 ohms).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Since the receiving antenna is not equally sensitive to signals received from all directions, the effective area is a function of the direction to the source.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Due to reciprocity (discussed above) the gain of an antenna used for transmitting must be proportional to its effective area when used for receiving.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Consider an antenna with no loss, that is, one whose electrical efficiency is 100%.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] It can be shown that its effective area averaged over all directions must be equal to λ2/4π, the wavelength squared divided by 4π.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Gain is defined such that the average gain over all directions for an antenna with 100% electrical efficiency is equal to 1.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] For an antenna with an efficiency of less than 100%, both the effective area and gain are reduced by that same amount.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Therefore, the above relationship between gain and effective area still holds.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] These are thus two different ways of expressing the same quantity.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] *A*eff is especially convenient when computing the power that would be received by an antenna of a specified gain, as illustrated by the above example.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The radiation pattern of an antenna is a plot of the relative field strength of the radio waves emitted by the antenna at different angles in the far field.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] It is typically represented by a three-dimensional graph, or polar plots of the horizontal and vertical cross sections.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The pattern of an ideal isotropic antenna, which radiates equally in all directions, would look like a sphere.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Many nondirectional antennas, such as monopoles and dipoles, emit equal power in all horizontal directions, with the power dropping off at higher and lower angles; this is called an omnidirectional pattern and when plotted looks like a torus or donut.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The radiation of many antennas shows a pattern of maxima or "*lobes*" at various angles, separated by "*nulls*", angles where the radiation falls to zero.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] This is because the radio waves emitted by different parts of the antenna typically interfere, causing maxima at angles where the radio waves arrive at distant points in phase, and zero radiation at other angles where the radio waves arrive out of phase.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In a directional antenna designed to project radio waves in a particular direction, the lobe in that direction is designed larger than the others and is called the "*main lobe*".
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The other lobes usually represent unwanted radiation and are called "*sidelobes*".
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The axis through the main lobe is called the "*principal axis*" or "*boresight axis*".
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The polar radiation patterns of Yagi antennas become narrower, and their directivity (and thus gain) increases, when they are designed for a relatively narrow frequency range, as compared with wideband designs.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The space surrounding an antenna can be divided into three concentric regions: The reactive near-field (also called the inductive near-field), the radiating near-field (Fresnel region) and the far-field (Fraunhofer) regions.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] These regions are useful to identify the field structure in each, although the transitions between them are gradual; there are no clear boundaries.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The orientation and physical structure of an antenna determine the *polarization* of the electric field of the radio wave transmitted by it.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] For instance, an antenna composed of a linear conductor (such as a dipole or whip antenna) oriented vertically will result in vertical polarization; if turned on its side the same antenna's polarization will be horizontal.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In the most general case, polarization is elliptical, meaning that over each cycle the electric field vector traces out an ellipse.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Two special cases are linear polarization (the ellipse collapses into a line) as discussed above, and circular polarization (in which the two axes of the ellipse are equal).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In linear polarization the electric field of the radio wave oscillates along one direction.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In circular polarization, the electric field of the radio wave rotates around the axis of propagation.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Circular or elliptically polarized radio waves are designated as right-handed or left-handed using the "thumb in the direction of the propagation" rule.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Note that for circular polarization, optical researchers use the opposite right-hand rule from the one used by radio engineers.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] It is best for the receiving antenna to match the polarization of the transmitted wave for optimum reception.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Otherwise there will be a loss of signal strength: when a linearly polarized antenna receives linearly polarized radiation at a relative angle of θ, then there will be a power loss of cos2θ .
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] A circularly polarized antenna can be used to equally well match vertical or horizontal linear polarizations, suffering a 3 dB signal reduction.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] However it will be blind to a circularly polarized signal of the opposite orientation.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Maximum power transfer requires matching the impedance of an antenna system (as seen looking into the transmission line) to the complex conjugate of the impedance of the receiver or transmitter.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The intended impedance is normally resistive, but a transmitter (and some receivers) may have limited additional adjustments to cancel a certain amount of reactance, in order to "tweak" the match.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The match is sought to minimize the amplitude of standing waves (measured via the standing wave ratio; SWR) that a mismatch raises on the line, and the increase in transmission line losses it entails.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Antenna tuning, in the strict sense of modifying the antenna itself, generally refers only to cancellation of any reactance seen at the antenna terminals, leaving only a resistive impedance which might or might not be exactly the desired impedance (that of the available transmission line).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Although an antenna may be designed to have a purely resistive feedpoint impedance (such as a dipole 97% of a half wavelength long) at just one frequency, this will very likely not be exactly true at other frequencies that the antenna is eventually used for.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In most cases, in principle the physical length of the antenna can be "trimmed" to obtain a pure resistance, although this is rarely convenient.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] On the other hand, the addition of a contrary inductance or capacitance can be used to cancel a residual capacitive or inductive reactance, respectively, and may be more convenient than lowering and trimming or extending the antenna, then hoisting it back.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In addition to those reactance-neutralizing add-ons, antennas of any kind may include a transformer and / or transformer balun at their feedpoint, to change the resistive part of the impedance to more nearly match the feedline's characteristic impedance.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] An additional problem is matching the remaining resistive impedance to the characteristic impedance of the transmission line: A general impedance matching network (an "antenna tuner" or ATU) will have at least two adjustable elements to correct both components of impedance.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Any matching network will have both power losses and power restrictions when used for transmitting.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Commercial antennas are generally designed to approximately match standard 50 Ohm coaxial cables, at standard frequencies; the design expectation is that a matching network will be merely used to 'tweak' any residual mismatch.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] In some cases matching is done in a more extreme manner, not simply to cancel a small amount of residual reactance, but to resonate an antenna whose resonance frequency is quite different from the intended frequency of operation.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The physically large inductor at the base of the antenna has an inductive reactance which is the opposite of the capacitative reactance that the short vertical antenna has at the desired operating frequency.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] (usually, but not always, for receiving) at a relatively low frequency, where it appears almost as a pure inductor.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] to produce a better-matched feedpoint resistance.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The loop is resonated by a coupled tuning capacitor, which is configured to match the receiver's tuning, in order to keep the antenna resonant at the chosen receive frequency over the AM broadcast band.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Ground reflections is one of the common types of multipath.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The radiation pattern and even the driving point impedance of an antenna can be influenced by the dielectric constant and especially conductivity of nearby objects.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] For a terrestrial antenna, the ground is usually one such object of importance.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The antenna's height above the ground, as well as the electrical properties (permittivity and conductivity) of the ground, can then be important.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Also, in the particular case of a monopole antenna, the ground (or an artificial ground plane) serves as the return connection for the antenna current thus having an additional effect, particularly on the impedance seen by the feed line.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] When an electromagnetic wave strikes a plane surface such as the ground, part of the wave is transmitted into the ground and part of it is reflected, according to the Fresnel coefficients.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] If the ground is a very good conductor then almost all of the wave is reflected (180° out of phase), whereas a ground modeled as a (lossy) dielectric can absorb a large amount of the wave's power.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The power remaining in the reflected wave, and the phase shift upon reflection, strongly depend on the wave's angle of incidence and polarization.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The dielectric constant and conductivity (or simply the complex dielectric constant) is dependent on the soil type and is a function of frequency.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] At lower mediumwave frequencies the ground acts mainly as a good conductor, which AM broadcast (0.5–1.7 MHz) antennas depend on.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] At frequencies between 3–30 MHz, a large portion of the energy from a horizontally polarized antenna reflects off the ground, with almost total reflection at the grazing angles important for ground wave propagation.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] That reflected wave, with its phase reversed, can either cancel or reinforce the direct wave, depending on the antenna height in wavelengths and elevation angle (for a sky wave).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] On the other hand, vertically polarized radiation is not well reflected by the ground except at grazing incidence or over very highly conducting surfaces such as sea water.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] However the grazing angle reflection important for ground wave propagation, using vertical polarization, is *in phase* with the direct wave, providing a boost of up to 6 dB, as is detailed below.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] At VHF and above (> 30 MHz) the ground becomes a poorer reflector.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] However, for shortwave frequencies, especially below ~15 MHz, it remains a good reflector especially for horizontal polarization and grazing angles of incidence.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] That is important as these higher frequencies usually depend on horizontal line-of-sight propagation (except for satellite communications), the ground then behaving almost as a mirror.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] The net quality of a ground reflection depends on the topography of the surface.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] When the irregularities of the surface are much smaller than the wavelength, the dominant regime is that of specular reflection, and the receiver sees both the real antenna and an image of the antenna under the ground due to reflection.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] But if the ground has irregularities not small compared to the wavelength, reflections will not be coherent but shifted by random phases.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] With shorter wavelengths (higher frequencies), this is generally the case.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] Whenever both the receiving or transmitting antenna are placed at significant heights above the ground (relative to the wavelength), waves reflected specularly by the ground will travel a longer distance than direct waves, inducing a phase shift which can sometimes be significant.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p01] When a sky wave is launched by such an antenna, that phase shift is always significant unless the antenna is very close to the ground (compared to the wavelength).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] The flow of current in wire antennas is identical to the solution of counter-propagating waves in a single conductor transmission line, which can be solved using the telegrapher's equations.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Unlike transmission lines, currents in antennas contribute power to the radiated part electromagnetic field, which can be modeled using radiation resistance.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] The combination of the incident and reflected wave, just as in a transmission line, forms a standing wave with a current node at the conductor's end, and a voltage node one-quarter wavelength from the end (if the element is at least that long).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] In a *resonant antenna*, the feedpoint of the antenna is at one of those voltage nodes.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Due to discrepancies from the simplified version of the transmission line model, the voltage one quarter wavelength from the current node is not exactly zero, but it is near a minimum, and small compared to the much larger voltage at the conductor's end.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Hence, a feed point matching the antenna at that spot requires a relatively small voltage but large current (the currents from the two waves add in-phase there), thus a relatively low feedpoint impedance.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Feeding the antenna at other points involves a large voltage, thus a large impedance, and usually one that is primarily reactive (low power factor), which is a terrible impedance match to available transmission lines.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Therefore, it is usually desired for an antenna to operate as a resonant element with each conductor having a length of one quarter wavelength (or any other odd multiples of a quarter wavelength).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] For instance, a half-wave dipole has two such elements (one connected to each conductor of a balanced transmission line) about one quarter wavelength long.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Depending on the conductors' diameters, a small deviation from this length is adopted in order to reach the point where the antenna current and the (small) feedpoint voltage are exactly in phase.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Then the antenna presents a purely resistive impedance, and ideally one close to the characteristic impedance of an available transmission line.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Despite these useful properties, resonant antennas have the disadvantage that they achieve resonance (purely resistive feedpoint impedance) only at a fundamental frequency, and perhaps some of its harmonics, and the feedpoint resistance is larger at higher-order resonances.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Therefore, resonant antennas can only achieve their good performance within a limited bandwidth, depending on the Q at the resonance.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] The electric and magnetic fields emanating from a driven antenna element will generally affect the voltages and currents in nearby antennas, antenna elements, or other conductors.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] This is particularly true when the affected conductor is a resonant element (multiple of half-wavelengths in length) at about the same frequency, as is the case where the conductors are all part of the same active or passive antenna array.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Thus using the mutual impedances calculated for a specific geometry, one can solve for the radiation pattern of a Yagi–Uda antenna or the currents and voltages for each element of a phased array.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Such an analysis can also describe in detail reflection of radio waves by a ground plane or by a corner reflector and their effect on the impedance (and radiation pattern) of an antenna in its vicinity.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Often such near-field interactions are undesired and pernicious.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Currents in random metal objects near a transmitting antenna will often be in poor conductors, causing loss of RF power in addition to unpredictably altering the characteristics of the antenna.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] By careful design, it is possible to reduce the electrical interaction between nearby conductors.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] For instance, the 90 degree angle in between the two dipoles composing the turnstile antenna ensures no interaction between these, allowing these to be driven independently (but actually with the same signal in quadrature phases in the turnstile antenna design).
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Antennas can be classified by operating principles or by their application.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] Different authorities placed antennas in narrower or broader categories.
[src:balun/antenna-electronics-p02] These antenna types and others are summarized in greater detail in the overview article, Antenna types, as well as in each of the linked articles in the list above, and in even more detail in articles which those link to.
[src:balun/balun] A **balun** /ˈbælʌn/ (from "balanced to unbalanced", originally, but now derived from "**balancing unit**") is an electrical device that allows balanced and unbalanced lines to be interfaced without disturbing the impedance arrangement of either line.
[src:balun/balun] A balun can take many forms and may include devices that also transform impedances but need not do so.
[src:balun/balun] Sometimes, in the case of transformer baluns, they use magnetic coupling but need not do so.
[src:balun/balun] Common-mode chokes are also used as baluns and work by eliminating, rather than rejecting, common mode signals.
[src:balun/balun] In classical transformers, there are two electrically separate windings of wire coils around the transformer's core.
[src:balun/balun] This type is sometimes called a 'voltage balun'.
[src:balun/balun] The primary winding receives the input signal, and the secondary winding puts out the converted signal.
[src:balun/balun] The core that they are wound on may either be empty (air core) or, equivalently, a magnetically neutral material like a porcelain support, or it may be a material which is good magnetic conductor like ferrite in modern high-frequency (HF) baluns, or soft iron as in the early days of telegraphy.
[src:balun/balun] The electrical signal in the primary coil is converted into a magnetic field in the transformer's core.
[src:balun/balun] When the electrical current through the primary reverses, it causes the established magnetic field to collapse.
[src:balun/balun] The collapsing magnetic field then induces an electric field in the secondary winding.
[src:balun/balun] The ratio of loops in each winding and the efficiency of the coils' magnetic coupling determines the ratio of electrical potential (voltage) to electrical current and the total power of the output.
[src:balun/balun] For idealized transformers, although the ratio of voltage to current will change in exact proportion to the square of the winding ratio, the power (measured in watts) remains identical.
[src:balun/balun] In real transformers, some energy is lost inside to heating of the metallic core of the transformer, to the AC and DC resistances of the winding conductors, and lost outside to the surrounding environment because of imperfect magnetic coupling between the two coils.
[src:balun/balun] An ideal balun consists of two wires (primary and secondary) and a core: the current in the primary wire generates a magnetic field in the core, which in turn induces an electric field in the secondary wire.
[src:balun/balun] An autotransformer balun has only one coil, or is made of two or more coils that have an electrical connection, wound around a core.
[src:balun/balun] One can also make an autotransformer from an ordinary transformer by cross-wiring the primary and secondary windings.
[src:balun/balun] Baluns made with autotransformer windings are also called *voltage baluns*, since they produce balanced output voltage, but not necessarily balanced current.
[src:balun/balun] In all autotransformers, the single winding must have at least one extra electrical connection – called a *tap* or *tap point* – between the two ends of the winding.
[src:balun/balun] The current sent into the balun through one pair of connections acts as if it were a primary coil, and magnetizes the entire core.
[src:balun/balun] When the electric current in the input segment of the coil changes, the induced magnetic field collapses and the collapse of the magnetic field in the core induces an electric current in the entire coil.
[src:balun/balun] Electrical connections to parts of the coil different from the input connections have higher or lower voltages depending on the length of the coil that the output is tapped from.
[src:balun/balun] Unlike transformer-type baluns, an autotransformer balun provides a path for DC current to ground from every terminal.
[src:balun/balun] Since outdoor antennas are prone to build-up of static electric charge, the path for the static to drain to ground through an autotransformer balun can be a distinct advantage.
[src:balun/balun] Transmission line or *choke* baluns can be considered as simple forms of transmission line transformers.
[src:balun/balun] This type is sometimes called a *current balun*, since it ensures equal current on both sides of its output, but not necessarily equal voltage.
[src:balun/balun] These are normally called ununs, because they go from unbalanced to unbalanced or un-un.
[src:balun/balun] Baluns are balanced to unbalanced or bal-un.
[src:balun/balun] A more subtle type results when the transformer type (magnetic coupling) is combined with the transmission line type (electro-magnetic coupling).
[src:balun/balun] Most typically the same kind of transmission line wires are used for the windings as carry the signal from the radio to the antenna, although these baluns can be made using any type of wire.
[src:balun/balun] The resulting devices have very wideband operation.
[src:balun/balun] *Transmission line transformers* commonly use small ferrite cores in toroidal rings or two-hole, binocular, shapes.
[src:balun/balun] The Guanella transmission line transformer (Guanella 1944) is often combined with a balun to act as an impedance matching transformer.
[src:balun/balun] Putting balancing aside a transformer of this type consists of a 75 Ω transmission line divided in parallel into two 150 Ω cables, which are then combined in series for 300 Ω.
[src:balun/balun] It is implemented as a specific wiring around the ferrite core of the balun.
[src:balun/balun] Classic magnetic transformers are limited in maximum frequency due to the permeability of the magnetic material, which declines rapidly above MHz frequencies.
[src:balun/balun] This limits the operating frequency to around 1 GHz.
[src:balun/balun] Microwave systems require baluns in the 1-100 GHz range for applications including mixers, push-pull amplifiers, and interface to differential analog to digital and digital to analog converters.
[src:balun/balun] Transmission line transformer baluns with a high frequency transmission line such as a wirewound pair are able to operate at significantly higher frequencies (to 8 GHz and above) by combining capacitive coupling with magnetic coupling typical of classic magnetic transformers.
[src:balun/balun] To operate at even higher frequencies, magnetic loading becomes ineffective.
[src:balun/balun] Nathan Marchand proposed a 'conversion transformer' that was capable of operation over a 1:3 bandwidth ratio in 1944.
[src:balun/balun] This basic circuit has been widely adapted and modified for use in planar structures (such as MMICs and RFICs) at frequencies up to at least 100 GHz.
[src:balun/balun] These types of planar baluns work exciting a mode in a ground plane or shield, which is then 'floated' away from the main ground.
[src:balun/balun] This allows extraction of the negative signal in addition to the main transmission line, creating positive and negative signal pairs.
[src:balun/balun] By connecting the positive and negative signal paths in various configurations dozens of balun configurations have been proposed and published in the electronics literature.
[src:balun/balun] The electrical connection of capacitance and inductance leads to a frequency where the electrical reactance of the self-inductance and self-capacitance in the balun are equal in magnitude but opposite in sign: that is, to resonance.
[src:balun/balun] A balun of any design operates poorly at or above its self-resonant frequency, and some of the design considerations for baluns are for the purpose of making the resonant frequency as far above the operating frequency as possible.
[src:balun/balun] An RF choke can be used in place of a balun.
[src:balun/balun] If a coil is made using coaxial cable near to the feed point of a balanced antenna, then the RF current that flows on the outer surface of the coaxial cable can be attenuated.
[src:balun/balun] One way of doing this would be to pass the cable through a ferrite toroid.
[src:balun/balun] The end result is exactly the same as a 1:1 current balun (or Guanella-type balun).
[src:balun/balun] A balun's function is generally to achieve compatibility between systems, and as such, finds extensive application in modern communications, particularly in realising frequency conversion mixers to make cellular phone and data transmission networks possible.
[src:balun/balun] They are also used to send an E1 carrier signal from coaxial cable (BNC connector, 1.0/2.3 connector, 1.6/5.6 connector, Type 43 connectors) to UTP CAT-5 cable or IDC connector.
[src:balun/balun] In television, amateur radio, and other antenna installations and connections, baluns convert between impedances and symmetry of feedlines and antennas.
[src:balun/balun] For example, transformation of 300-Ω twin-lead or 450-Ω ladder line (balanced) to 75-Ω coaxial cable (unbalanced), or to directly connect a balanced antenna to unbalanced coaxial cable.
[src:balun/balun] To avoid feed line radiation, baluns are typically used as a form of common mode choke attached at the antenna feed point to prevent the coaxial cable from acting as an antenna and radiating power.
[src:balun/balun] This typically is needed when a balanced antenna (for instance, a dipole) is fed with coax; without a balun, the shield of the coax could couple with one side of the dipole, inducing common mode current, and becoming part of the antenna and unintentionally radiating.
[src:balun/balun] In measuring the impedance or radiation pattern of a balanced antenna using a coaxial cable, it is important to place a balun between the cable and the antenna feed.
[src:balun/balun] Unbalanced currents that may otherwise flow on the cable will make the measured antenna impedance sensitive to the configuration of the feed cable, and the radiation pattern of small antennas may be distorted by radiation from the cable.
[src:balun/balun] Baluns are present in radars, transmitters, satellites, in every telephone network, and probably in most wireless network modem/routers used in homes.
[src:balun/balun] It can be combined with transimpedance amplifiers to compose high-voltage amplifiers out of low-voltage components.
[src:balun/balun] Baseband video uses frequencies up to several megahertz.
[src:balun/balun] A balun can be used to couple video signals to twisted-pair cables instead of using coaxial cable.
[src:balun/balun] Many security cameras now have both a balanced unshielded twisted pair (UTP) output and an unbalanced coaxial one via an internal balun.
[src:balun/balun] A balun is also used on the video recorder end to convert back from the 100 Ω balanced to 75 Ω unbalanced.
[src:balun/balun] A balun of this type has a BNC connector with two screw terminals.
[src:balun/balun] VGA/DVI baluns are baluns with electronic circuitry used to connect VGA/DVI sources (laptop, DVD, etc.) to VGA/DVI display devices over long runs of CAT-5/CAT-6 cable.
[src:balun/balun] Runs over 130 m (400 ft) may lose quality because of attenuation and variations in the arrival time of each signal.
[src:balun/balun] A skew control and special low skew or skew free cable is used for runs over 130 m (400 ft).
[src:balun/balun] In audio applications, baluns serve multiple purposes: they can convert between high-impedance unbalanced and low impedance balanced lines.
[src:balun/balun] Another application is decoupling of devices (avoidance of earth loops).
[src:balun/balun] A third application of baluns in audio systems is in the provision of balanced mains power to the equipment.
[src:balun/balun] This noise infiltrates the audio/video system through the power supplies and raises the noise floor of the entire system.
[src:balun/balun] Except for the connections, the three devices in the image are electrically identical, but only the leftmost two can be used as baluns.
[src:balun/balun] The device on the left would normally be used to connect a high impedance source, such as a guitar, into a balanced microphone input, serving as a passive DI unit.
[src:balun/balun] The one in the center is for connecting a low impedance balanced source, such as a microphone, into a guitar amplifier.
[src:balun/balun] The one at the right is not a balun, as it provides only impedance matching.
